<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New "Mad Cow" Case Found in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The French Agriculture Ministry said
today that it has identified a new case of "mad cow" disease,
formally known as Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), in
central France.
</P>
<P>
The case, the ninth this year and the 22nd since 1990, was
found in a herd of 155 cows of a diary farm in the Cantal region
south of Clermont Ferrand, and the herd in question has been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Scientists found that BSE, which reached epidemic proportions
in the late 1980s, was caused by feeding cattle the remains of
sheeps that had been infected with scrapie, their own version of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
The disease reportedly continues to infect British herds
despite a government ban on using feed containing animal protein
</P>
<P>
After a possible link was discovered between BSE and the human
brain-wasting disease Creutzfeldt-Jacobs Disease, the European
Union adopted an overall ban on March 27 this year against
Britain's beef exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
