<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large-scale AIDS Vaccine Tests on Humans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Though an AIDS vaccine is possible,
it is too early to begin large-scale tests on humans, an expert
told the 11th International AIDS Conference in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
"HIV is simply too complex and wily an opponent" to be beaten
by the simple types of vaccines that controlled polio and
smallpox, said Dr. John Moore of the U.S. Aaron Diamond AIDS
Research Center.
</P>
<P>
"While recent studies show vaccinations can protect chimpanzees
and tests are indicating humans can be immunized safely, many
fundamental questions need to be answered," he was quoted as
saying by a local press report today.
</P>
<P>
There has been reports that the first large trial of AIDS
inoculation is scheduled to begin next year in northern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
But Dr. Edward Mbidde of the Uganda Cancer Institute argued
that AIDS is such a threat to the developing world that "we need
anything that would make a dent in the epidemic."
</P>
<P>
"Even a vaccine with low efficacy will help," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 10,000 people, 90 percent of them in
developing world, are infected with AIDS virus each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
