<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Mad Cow" Crisis to Cost EU 2.1 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The beef industry crisis, stirred
up by the British "mad cow" fears which plagued eventually the
whole world, will cost the European Union (EU) some 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars, EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler said
today.
</P>
<P>
Fischler blamed beef traders for their failure to pass on the
sharp fall in beef prices to consumers, an act which could have
helped bring consumption back to pre-crisis levels and make up the
huge losses EU suffered.
</P>
<P>
Though the European Commission has so far taken 120,000 metric
tons of beef off the market under its intervention procedures and
even 600,000 tons by the end of the year, the market, the key
solution to the crisis, should never be neglected, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU no longer has the option of offloading beef stocks onto
world markets because of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT) rules restricting on export subsidies.
</P>
<P>
Fischler said the EU commission is urgently examining ways of
cutting production and boosting consumption, adding that without
additional radical and immediate action to cut beef production and
boost consumption, "the situation can only deteriorate further."
</P>
<P>
Beef consumption in the EU has fallen by 11 percent since the
British government's announcement in March of a possible link
between bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and a fatal human
brain disease, which kicked off a "mad cow" crisis worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The wholesale beef prices fell by 7 to 14 percent which
influenced the retail prices in most European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
