<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Start Photo Film Talks in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the United States
and Japan started on Wednesday an initial round of bilateral talks
under the auspices of the World Trade Organization (WTO) to sort
out a photo film trade dispute between them.
</P>
<P>
The talks, sought by the United States as the first step to set
in motion the dispute settlement procedure of the WTO, will be
held in Geneva, where the WTO based, for two days, trade officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Washington filed a complaint with the WTO on June 13, accusing
the Japanese government of "unreasonable practices" that lock out
foreign products from the Japanese consumer photo film and paper
market.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth complaint filed by the U.S. against Japan
since establishment of the WTO in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The essence of the U.S. complaint is that the government of
Japan intentionally created a set of interlocking barriers (to
foreign film products) to counteract its commitments under the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) and other
international agreements," said U.S. chief negotiator James
Southwick Wednesday at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"Those barrier continue to be in place and continue to restrict
market access," added Southwick, who is also U.S. Deputy Assistant
Trade Representative for Japan.
</P>
<P>
Washington took the case to the WTO after an 11-month
investigation into U.S. Film maker Eastman Kodak Co's petition
charging that Japan's Fuji Photo Film Co. and the Japanese
government have been collaborating to block access to the Japanese
market.
</P>
<P>
Specificly, Washington complained that Japan's Premiums and
Misrepresentation Law restricts the use of sales incentives by
foreign companies trying to break into Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
It also argued that the Large-Scale Retail Store Law of Japan,
which regulates the size and operating hours of department stores
and other large retailers, constitutes a serious barrier for Kodak
and other foreign companies, violating WTO's General Agreement on
Trade in Services.
</P>
<P>
Accord to Southwick, the consultations will start with the
second issue Wednesday afternoon and will tackle the first issue
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese officials expect to prove that there is no
discrimination against foreign products in the Japanese market.
They will also try to show that the retail store law doesn't
violate the services agreement and has nothing to do with a
decline in Kodak's Japanese market share, trade sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also demands bilateral talks with Japan outside of WTO
dispute settlement proceedings to discuss what it considers to be
restrictive private-sector business practices in Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Southwick, the two sides were unable to
schedule this consultation in this round and he hoped that they
could enter into consultations on this issue in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. negotiator declined to speculate on what kind of
outcome could be expected from this round of talks. "We'll try to
explaining our views and address questions from the other side.
Beyond that it is difficult to predict," he said.
</P>
<P>
If the bilateral talks can not reach an agreement within 60
days, The U.S. can ask the WTO to set up a panel to rule over the
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
