<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Food Distribution Plan Ready for UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council's
sanctions committee has completed the final draft of procedures of
Iraq's limited oil exports and imports of humanitarian supplies in
accordance with the Iraqi-U.N. oil-for-food deal, the Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The INA quoted German Ambassador Antonius Eitel, head of the
U.N. sanctions committee, as expressing his belief that approvals
of the committee member-states will reach the United Nations
within two days for final endorsement Friday.
</P>
<P>
Following Iraq's presentation of its food distribution plan to
the U.N., the United States which takes a tough stance on Iraq has
opposed the plan. It accused Iraq of trying to translate the plan
into other purposes. Iraq has blamed the U.S. for impeding the
immediate implementation of the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The German ambassador attributed the delay in the formulation
of the draft plan to the sensitive issues related to the respect of
Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's chief negotiator to the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food talks
stressed that both Iraq and the U.N. are keen to ensure the quick
implementation of the memorandum of understanding reached by Iraq
and the U.N. on May 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the memorandum of understanding, Iraq is
permitted to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six
months to but its desperately needed food, medicine and other
humanitarian materials. Iraq must obtain the Security Council's
approval of its food distribution plan before the oil-for-food
deal goes into effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
