<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Not Welcome in Okinawa: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Okinawan governor Masahide Ota told
Japan's Supreme Court here today that the Okinawan people now are
tired of the U.S. military presence on the island.
</P>
<P>
Ota appeared before the court's all 15 judges to defend his
refusal to cooperate with the Japanese government over its drive
to renew leases to the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
He said that his decision resulted from his responsibility to
protect the Okinawa's islanders.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa has long borne an unfair share of the U.S. military
presence in Japan, said he, adding that Tokyo should stop the
policy that forces the islanders to lease their land.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa hosts some 75 percent of the 47,000 U.S. troops in
Japan, and the U.S. bases amount to 20 percent of its area.
</P>
<P>
The people of Okinawa have long complained about the heavy
concentration of the U.S. bases on the island, but it was the rape
of an Okinawan schoolgirl by three U.S. servicemen last year that
sparked the landowners' protests against the continued U.S.
military presence on the island, 1,600 kilometers southwest of
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Under the growing pressure from Okinawa, the United States has
agreed with Japan in April to reduce about 20 percent of the land
it currently uses in Okinawa in the coming five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
