<HEADLINE> More Indian Politicians Charged in Hawala Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 10 (Xinhua) -- In a major development, India's
Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) today charged five more
politicians in the 18 million US dollar hawala bribery scandal,
which has rocked the country's entire political arena earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Press Trust of India, the CBI filed charge
sheets against former Uttar Pradesh governor Moti Lal Vora, former
Kerala governor P. Shiv Shankar, one former minister and two top
bureaucrats on charges of receiving massive amounts of money from
illegal foreign exchange dealers (hawala dealers).
</P>
<P>
The special court dealing with the case issued summons to all
the five accused to present themselves before the court on July
19.
</P>
<P>
With these five fresh charge sheets, the total number of
politicians charged by the CBI in the hawala case rose to 30.
</P>
<P>
The first two rounds of charge sheets were issued on January 16
and February 22 respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
