<HEADLINE> Hurricane Drives Thousands to Evacuate N.C. Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 residents and
tourists on the barrier islands in North Carolina began to
evacuate Wednesday, expecting Hurricane Bertha to land the eastern
coastal area soon.
</P>
<P>
Emergency officials in South Carolina also urged residents to
leave coastal Beaufort County, fearing that storm surges could
wash out bridges and low-lying areas, the Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation came as the entire Carolinas' coast and part of
Georgia were under a hurricane watch, expecting Bertha, packing
105 mph winds, to come close to the area within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service also issued a tropical storm
warning for Florida as the hurricane was moving toward northwest
from the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
Forecasters earlier had predicted that Bertha would stay clear
of the United States but they changed the forecast Tuesday. At 8
a.m. EDT Wednesday, Bertha was about 55 miles east of Eleuthera
Island in the middle of the 700-island Bahamas archipelago, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
There were about 40,000 residents and summer visitors on the
Hatteras Island and about 10,000 people, mostly tourists, were on
Ocracoke Island before the evacuation, emergency management
officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
