<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Says It Follows Situation in Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is
following with "a lot of attention" the situation in Niger after
General Ibrahim Bare Mainassara, head of the country's military
junta, dissolved the Independent National Electorate Commission
(CENI).
</P>
<P>
Yves Doutriaux, vice-spokesman of the French Foreign Ministry,
said that "things which happened in the past 48 hours, notably the
dissolution of the CENI (on Monday) during counting of the votes,
have raised questions."
</P>
<P>
He said that "the French government has always hoped that the
voting go on in transparency so that the outcomes would be
incontestable and undisputed."
</P>
<P>
General Ibrahim Bare Mainassara was elected in the first round
of election on Sunday and Monday with 52.22 percent of votes,
according to the National Commission of Elections which has
replaced the CENI.
</P>
<P>
Mainassar has been in power since January after ejecting
President Mahamane Ousmane. Ousmane also ran in the election.
</P>
<P>
The United States Monday criticized the dissolution of CENI,
saying this had jeopardized the credibility of the elections and
would throw a doubt on outcomes of the voting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
