<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Army to Cut 38 Regiments in 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The French Army will cut 38
regiments from a total of 180 in the next three years and the Air
Force will close five bases next year, said the French daily Le
Monde today.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Minister Charles Million is to announce next
Wednesday a package of "measures for adaptation" to reform the
country's defense system as was announced by President Jacques
Chirac earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde said in its Friday edition that among the regiments to
be cut are the military academy regiments, the instruction school
of armoured ground force and the cavalry at Saumur.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the 2000-2002 period, the commanding
structures and support systems of the French armed forces will
also put under restructuring programs.
</P>
<P>
The reduction will decrease France's army deployment in Germany
from 20,000 to 3,000, and throw doubts over the future of the
Eurocorps, said Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in 1997, the air force will close five of
its 44 bases, including those in Chartres of Eure-et-Loir, Cenon
in Gironde. Toul in Meurthe-et-Moselle, Limoges in Haute-Vienne
and the plateau of Albion in Vaucluse which shelters strategic
nuclear missiles now.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French Navy will also be reorganized along with
the restructuring of its arsenals, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to a law on military programing, the country's
defense system will cut 24 percent of its forces. That will bring
about a 35 percent reduction of the ground force, a 24 percent cut
of the air force and a 20 percent cut of the navy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
