<HEADLINE> Karpov Retains FIDE Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian grandmaster Anatoly Karpov
retained his World Chess Federation (FIDE) title on Thursday when
he drew with U.S. challenger Gata Kamsky in the 18th game in
Elista.
</P>
<P>
The draw brought the score to 10.5 points to 7.5 points,
giving the Russian an unassailable lead in the 20-game series.
</P>
<P>
The game was continued on Thursday after being adjourned on
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
World number one Gary Kasparov, who broke away in 1993 to
found his own Professional Chess Association (PCA) did not take
part in the FIDE competition. 
</P>
