<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Unveils Internet Regulation Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Government
unveiled today a scheme to regulate the Internet, the master
network of the global computer networks, which now has over 40
million subscribers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the Class License Scheme for regulating the
Internet at a press conference today, the Singapore Broadcasting
Authority (SBA) reiterated its commitment to "safeguard the
interest of the Internet community while promoting the healthy
development of the industry."
</P>
<P>
The scheme, which takes effect next Monday, aims to encourage
responsible use of the Internet while facilitating its healthy
development in Singapore, the SBA said.
</P>
<P>
"It encourages minimum standards in cyberspace and seeks to
protect Net users, particularly the young, against the broadcast
of unlawful or objectionable materials," it explained.
</P>
<P>
The automatic licensing scheme will cover Internet Service
Providers and Internet Content Providers. Under the conditions of
the license, these providers are obligated to assist the SBA with
any relevant information on persons who violated the rules. It
will focus on groups which provide content pages on an organized
basis.
</P>
<P>
"SBA will focus on content which may undermine public morals,
political stability and religious harmony of Singapore. However,
SBA recognizes that it is impossible to regulate the Internet
fully," the SBA said.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the success of Internet regulation will depend
very much on industry self-regulation and community action.
"Singaporeans can help SBA in the identification of objectionable
sites in order to keep cyberspace clean," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
