<HEADLINE> US Official to Visit Cyprus Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. permanent representative to
the U.N. Madeleine Albright will visit Cyprus to follow up the
discussions on the Cyprus issue between Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides and U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington last month,
a U.S. diplomat said here today.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus, Kenneth Brill, was speaking
after his first meeting with Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides,
soon after presenting his credentials to President Glafcos
Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Brill, who arrived here Tuesday, and Michaelides discussed
Albright's tour of Nicosia, Athens and Ankara between July 16-19,
accompanied by U.S. presidential emissary for Cyprus Richard
Beattie.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on press reports that Albright will be
bringing some ideas on the Cyprus problem, Brill said, "She is
coming here to help advance the process that was discussed in
Washington."
</P>
<P>
He added that she will be "following up those discussions and
see how we can move the process further ahead."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus News Agency (CNA) today quoted U.S. State Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns as saying that Albright brings with her
some American ideas about the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
She will try to "inject into the Cyprus situation some ideas
to try to resolve the more than 20 years old diplomatic problem,"
Burns told CNA.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Albright's trip as "very significant," Brill
noted that the focus of this trip will be Cyprus but she "has
other responsibilities as well so she will also be discussing
other issues."
</P>
<P>
The new American ambassador reiterated President Clinton's
personal commitment to helping the efforts for solving the
protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, presenting his credentials to President Clerides
today, the new U.S. ambassador assured Cyprus that his country
will continue "to work closely with the United Nations and others,
to help the Cypriot people achieve an acceptable solution to the
Cyprus problem, based on a bizonal, bicommunal federation."
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated the determination of the Clinton
Administration "to help, in any way it can, promote a just and
lasting settlement to the Cyprus problem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
