<HEADLINE> EU Citizens Allowed to Be Hired in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Greek parliament today approved a
bill enabling citizens of European Union member-states to be hired
in the public sector in Greece provided they have a knowledge of
the Greek language.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of the Interior Ministry George Moraitis said
the bill brought national legislation in line with the community
law, clarifying that the relevant presidential decree to be issued
would specify those positions which would remain closed to
non-Greeks.
</P>
<P>
These include positions in the armed forces, security services,
tax services, diplomatic corps and judiciary.
</P>
<P>
The European court earlier this month issued a judgement
condemning Greece for violating article 48 of the Maastricht Treaty
concerning the free movement of people between member-states as
well as community regulations on the hiring of citizens from other
member-states in the public sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
