<HEADLINE> Funeral, Interment Regulations Adopted in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- New rules banning burials in
farmland around Beijing have been adapted, as part of a major
reform in funeral arrangements in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing provisional regulations on the management of
funeral and interment were agreed at a meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress today.
</P>
<P>
The Regulations, which will come into force on October 1, are
intended to step up the reforms of funerals and interments,
protect land resources, and advance cultural and ideological
progress in China's capital.
</P>
<P>
The Regulations specify measures to manage funerals and
interments, the storage of ashes, and the construction of
cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Regulations, the municipal government
will exercise tighter control over the establishment of
cemeteries, which must be built on barren mountain sides or barren
land, and may not be built on farmland.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's meeting, Liu Baocheng, director of the
Beijing Municipal Civil Affairs Bureau, said that Beijing
currently has 12 funeral parlors and 22 cemeteries, which employ a
total of 1,000 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
