<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cabbies Not Excited About Fare Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Atlanta cab drivers said Wednesday
that the 4 dollars flat-rate fare increase for the Olympics won't
help much but they will willy-nilly accept it.
</P>
<P>
"This little flat rate isn't going to cover anything," said a
47-year-old cab driver.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Bill Campbell signed legislation just before midnight
Tuesday that enacted the increase, in effect until August 30.
</P>
<P>
The mayor had vetoed a more costly increase passed by the City
Council.
</P>
<P>
The flat rate for one passenger from the airport to the
downtown, for example, went from 18 dollars to 22.
</P>
<P>
The higher fares are hardly enough compensate for big traffic
jams, cabbies say. "It's going to take people longer to go
places," said Nathan Whatley, a superviser for Georgia Cab Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
