<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Parliament Approves New Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's
half-Moslem-half-Christian parliament approved today a new
election bill, paving the way for those desiring a place in the
128-seat house to prepare themselves for running for the election
next month.
</P>
<P>
After three days of hot debates, the Lebanese unicameral
parliament ratified the bill by an overwhelming majority without
introducing a major amendment.
</P>
<P>
The election bill divides the country into four constituencies
tantamount to the governorates of Beirut, the North, the South and
Bekaa, excepting the fifth governorate of Mount Lebanon where
elections will be held on the basis of the six districts it
consists of.
</P>
<P>
Oppositions to the division mainly came from Christians
arguing that it was designed to ensure the election of Walid
Jumblat, leader of the Shouf mountain-based small Druze
community, who is a political ally of Prime Minister Rafik
al-Hariri and an intimate friend of the Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
However, the parliament approved the controversial bill despite
prevalent fears that the Lebanese powerful Christian community
would be disencouraged to participate in the election since the
guaranteed election of Jumblat and his friends would reduce
chances of independent Christians who might otherwise be elected
to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Most Christians and some Moslems boycotted the 1992
parliamentary election on the grounds that there could be no just
elections in this country with a presence of foreign forces
(referring to the Syrian military existence) on the lands.
</P>
<P>
In his debate during the parliament's general session, Selim
Hoss, the former prime minister, said that the bill was in breach
of the 1989 Taif accord for national reconciliation which ended
the 1975-90 civil war and which stated that all electoral
districts should be based on Lebanon's five governorates.
</P>
<P>
Before becoming a law, the election bill still needs a
signature of President Elias Hrawi. After the approval in the
parliament, the bill is expected to be immediately handed over to
the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The election activities are scheduled to begin on August 18 and
will go through the next four weeks. The formal schedule will be
officially announced soon by Interior Minister Michel Al-Murr.
</P>
<P>
Even before a green light given by the government, some
impatient candidates have hung out their pictures in the
capital's streets since a week ago.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Christian mainstream Phalange Party announced
13 candidates to run for election throughout the country. Six
others had been formally declared earlier by the Lebanese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
According to the Lebanese constitution, the president must
always be a Maronite Catholic, the house speaker a Moslem Shiite
and the prime minister a Moslem Sunni. And the seats of the
parliament are distributed among the 17 religious or sectarian
communities roughly in accordance with their population
proportions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
