<HEADLINE> Islamic States Opposed to Israeli Spy Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Islamic countries declared here
today that they stand opposed to the activities of the Israeli
spy satellite which endanger peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
That is one of the seven decisions adopted at the closing
session of the third ministerial meeting on posts and
telecommunications of the member states of the Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Some 40 OIC member states participated in the two-day
ministerial meeting held here, which recognized that postal and
telecommunications services are important elements of cooperation
in various fields among OIC member states.
</P>
<P>
However, an official from the Turkish delegation told Xinhua
that his delegation has not discussed the article about the
Israeli spy satellite activities.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish official, who spokes on condition of anonymity,
said, "Iran put the stuff into the document at last minute. The
meeting has not made any concrete results, only wishes and empty
talks."
</P>
<P>
According to the Tehran Declaration on the development of
posts and telecommunications adopted at this ministerial meeting,
the OIC member states will do their utmost to accord assistance to
the Palestinian people for the restoration of their inalienable
rights in liberating their homeland from occupation and the
establishment of an independent state in their entire land with
Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to exchange expertise in the field of posts
and telecommunications between OIC member states to enhance
bilateral and multilateral cooperation among themselves and
especially with regard to the priorities of national development.
</P>
<P>
The OIC member states also declared that they will pursue
economic and commercial cooperation among themselves to expand
and enhance their economy.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Iran and other Islamic countries voiced their
urgent need to develop satellite communication and information
highway in a bid not to leg behind the modern society.
</P>
<P>
Representatives reviewed the major telecommunications issues of
the Islamic countries and explored practical ways to promote
international cooperation in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
