<HEADLINE> Security Added for Atlanta Water Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Soldiers, police and hidden
cameras have been employed to monitor reservoirs, water towers and
underground storage tanks to ensure that no one tampers with metro
Atlanta's water supply during the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Fences with barbed wire have also been constructed around water
treatment areas and intake facilities that bring water from the
Chattahoochee River and other rivers and streams into the drinking
water system.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Atlanta area water authorities are
disclosing very litte about the high-tech security measures being
taken to deter terroists and pranksters.
</P>
<P>
Water authorities apparently have two worries: threats to water
purity, and threats to the delivery of the water itself. Hot
weather and drought already have many of metro Atlanta's 15
systems operating at the edge of capacity.
</P>
<P>
"We are removing our ladders from tanks and bolting down any
trapdoors," said Marcellus Pitts, a manager of water
infrastructure here. "We have to be proactive or somebody could
drop something in the water."
</P>
<P>
The city of Atlanta is taking the most drastic measures. A
security force of 53 soldiers and police will patrol the
facilities 24 hours a day. The Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency will be
conducting toxicity tests around the clock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
