<HEADLINE> King Hussein Supports Government's Efforts to Lift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan expressed
here today his full support for the government's efforts to lift
subsidies on bread.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here today by Prime Minister Abdul
Karim Kabariti on floating the price of bread, King Hussein
praised the prime minister's courage to take the bold move.
</P>
<P>
In the midst of the press conference, King Hussein appeared
suddenly and attended part of it.
</P>
<P>
His presence was seen as a strong support to the government
and his great attention to the thorny issue.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for all citizens to make sacrifice in
order to achieve self-reliance and strongly accused the
opposition parties of harming national interests by opposing the
government's move.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to go on building the homeland, every citizen should
reconsider his views, believes and stands and should put them on
the right track, said King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
He recalled the situation in 1989, when riots occurred in
several Jordanian cities after the government had imposed price
rises of between 15 percent and 50 percent on basic goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
He warned against the resurgence of the grave situation.
</P>
<P>
The king said Jordan was the first country in the world to
shoulder its responsibilities when it received waves of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
He added the country has centered on education, health,
communications and other important fields to give the Jordanian
citizens a chance to be more productive.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kabariti said the government will fix all the
issues relating to the price increase of bread and announce the
decision "in a couple of days."
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that the move will not be implemented
until after setting all necessary mechanism and arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti reiterated that the Jordanian citizens will be
compensated for the increase in the price of bread.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he believed people will support the
government's move once the "misunderstanding and
misinterpretation" were solved.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Information Minister Marwan Muasher Wednesday
announced the government's detailed plans to lift subsidies on
bread, saying that the price hike will not affect citizens'
standard of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
