<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Faces Population Explosion (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian authorities today
sounded the alarm for a danger of population explosion as 25
million youngsters under 17 are approaching the age of marriage.
</P>
<P>
Ali Reza Marandi, Minister of Health and Medical Care, said
"We will have another phase of high population growth in the
future and we are very much concerned about the situation."
</P>
<P>
"There are a large number of children under 16 or 17 and they
are reaching gradually the age of marriage. In other words, 25
million youngsters mean 12.5 million couples in the future. If
each couple have two children, still they will add 25 million to
the population," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is my concern. But we are doing our best to educate our
people through mass media in order to decrease the growth rate,"
said the minister in an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Today is the World Population Day. Some 1,000 people,
specialists and government officials gathered here to explore ways
of birth control in the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
The past 20 years witnessed a fast growth of population which
has been doubled from 34 million in 1976 to 64 million in
Iran. However, the oil export income decreased twice for the
country. The population growth has posed a grave threat to the
development of the national economy and other social development.
</P>
<P>
Specialists warned that the population would be doubled again
in 20 or 25 years, thus naturally aggravating the conditions and
pressure upon the decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Vice-President Hamid Mirzadeh said at today's seminar
"our large population is consuming 75 percent of our resources
while only 20-25 percent goes to long-term development."
</P>
<P>
Xu Shuyun, representative of the United Nations Population Fund
in Tehran, said at the meeting that the United Nations supports
Iran's population and family planning program. "UNFPA will
continue, as in the past, its fruitful cooperation with Iran's
relevant ministries and organizations in order to achieve our
common goals in the field of population and development."
</P>
<P>
Mohaqiq Damad, a leading clergyman and head of Iran's General
Accounting Office, said, "The population growth rate is not a
religious issue in Iran," arguing that the notion that Islam
encourages population growth is an utter misconception and a "pure
lie."
</P>
<P>
Actually, the family planning was a taboo in the Islamic
Republic about eight years ago. Some doctors were even executed
for carrying out abortion operations for women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0052 </DOCNO>
