<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-Mail Roommates In Court Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's first case of suspected
E-mail abuse has been heard by the Haidian District People's Court
of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The case, the first of its kind in China, was launched after a
Chinese student missed a chance-in-a-lifetime opportunity to study
in the USA.
</P>
<P>
Michigan University, which had offered an 18,000 US dollar
scholarship to Xue Yange, gave the place to somebody else after
receiving an e-mail message on the world Internet.
</P>
<P>
The allegation is that Xue's roommate, Zhang Nan, sent the
e-mail declining the university place.
</P>
<P>
The two young women are classmates in the Psychology Department
of the famous Beijing University. Both of them are due to graduate
this summer with master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
In early April Xue received an e-mail message from Michigan
University, telling her she had been granted a scholarship of
18,000 U.S. dollars for further training.
</P>
<P>
While waiting for a formal notice, Xue was told April 27 that
an e-mail in her name had been sent to the American university,
informing them that she had chosen other university, and declining
the scholarship. Michigan University then decided to consider
other candidates for the scholarship.
</P>
<P>
Xue said that Michigan University was the only American
university that had promised to give her scholarship.
</P>
<P>
She suspected Zhang of writing the electronic-letter, and filed
a case which was accepted for hearing by the Haidian District
People's Court. She cited violation of her name.
</P>
<P>
Zhang admitted that she did send three e-mails from the
university laboratory on April 12. One of them was sent to a
friend in the United States, four minutes before the e-mail to
Michigan University was sent out. But Zhang denied that the
message to the university was written or sent by her.
</P>
<P>
Xue and Zhang shared the same e-mail address, which belonged to
Zhang's tutor.
</P>
<P>
Zhang told the court that six or seven American universities
had informed her that they would grant her scholarships. She chose
one and refused the rest.
</P>
<P>
Zhang read one of the letters to the court, to show that there
was no similarity in the grammar of her letter, and the one sent
to Michigan University. Xue had claimed that the grammar of the
letter to Michigan University accorded with the grammatical style
of Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The plaintiff is also claiming 15,000 yuan (about 1,807
U.S. dollars) in compensation for spiritual loss and suffering.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that she will file a cross-charge against the
plaintiff for defaming her reputation by making the allegations.
</P>
<P>
The court decided after debate to postpone the announcement
of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese learned about the Internet in December 1993 when
Zhu Ling, a student from Beijing-based Qinghua University, was
found seriously poisoned by a mystery substance. While Zhu was in
hospital some of her classmates went to the Internet for help. The
information received from various parts of the world provided help
to enable medics to make an accurate diagnosis, and then
administer life-saving treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
