<HEADLINE> Groups Within UPC Differ on Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Two groups within Uganda People's
Congress (UPC),the biggest opposition party in Uganda, have
released contradictory statements on the leadership of the party
President Milton Obote, local paper "the New Vision" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Presidential Policy Commission (PPC) James
Rwanyarare blamed his predecessor Ceieilia Ogwal for "Questioning
the legitimate awthority of the PPC and the party president."
</P>
<P>
Jamer Rwanyarare and his followers said yesterday that the National
Task Force (NTF)was onlu an ad hoc organ created to mobilize
for the 1996 election of the party.
</P>
<P>
But mrs. Ogwal and her swpporters rejected the appointment of
Rwanyarare as the chairman of the PPC and decribed the National
Task Force (NTF) as the supreme organ of the UPC.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference yesterday, the Ogwal growp said, "Obote
will remain with his title. We shall either take his advice or
not, but we shall deal with the situation as it arises in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the group Patrick Mwondha said the interim
excutive council headed by Ogwal will exert its authority on all
members of UPC inlcuding Obote.
</P>
<P>
Employees at the party secretariat in Uganda House said there
had been no normal operations in UPC other than trade of
accusations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
