<HEADLINE> Israeli Prime Minister to Visit Jordan Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan announced here today that
the newly elected Israeli Prime Minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, will
pay an official visit to the Kingdom next week.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference here today, Prime Minister Abdul Karim
Kabariti said Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu will visit Amman
next week, the first by Netanyahu in the capacity of prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti said the two sides will discuss the Middle East peace
process, the principle of land-for-peace and other spirits set
in the 1991 Madrid peace conference and agreed upon by all parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister described the upcoming visit of Netanyahu
as "very important."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Natanyahu's visit in Washington, Kabariti said
there are some "positive" results of the talks between the Israeli
prime minister and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Jordan agrees with the Israeli position on
security, saying that "there will be no peace without security."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that "a durable peace must be just and
comprehensive."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added that during the talks the two sides
will also deal with the issues of Jerusalem and the Jewish
settlement, on which they hold different views.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kabariti disclosed King Hussein will visit Syria and
Saudi Arabia soon.
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate, saying that the time of the visits
will be set by King Hussein in his direct contacts with the two
leaders respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
