<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Gets Bigger Slice in Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine defense sector got
the biggest share in the proposed 476.2 billion peso (18.3 billion
US dollar) 1997 national budget.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, the defense allocation for
1997 was placed at 37.2 billion pesos (1.4 billion US dollars)
from 30.9 billion pesos (1.2 billion US dollars) in 1996, a growth
of 20.4 percent which is even higher than the percentage growth of
the allocation for social services.
</P>
<P>
In a recent memorandum to President Fidel Ramos, Budget and
Management Secretary Salvador Enriquez, jr. said the increase in
the defense budget resulted from the "substantial increases in
personal services arising from salary adjustments for defense
personnel."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the defense sector accounted for 7.2 percent of the
total budget, and in the 1997 budget proposal, the defense slice
will grow to 7.8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
