<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helping Hands for Zhejiang Flood-Stricken Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Electricity supplies,
communications and telecommunications services in most of the
flood-stricken areas in east China's Zhejiang Province have
resumed, due to the work of hundreds of relief teams.
</P>
<P>
The floods, caused by heavy rainfall from June 30 to July 6,
caused damages to dozens of counties in north Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Branch of the People's Insurance Company of China
is expected to pay 300 million yuan (36 million US dollars) in
compensation for the flood-stricken areas, and 10 million yuan has
been distributed to flood victims and enterprises that have
reported losses, according to a source with the insurance company.
</P>
<P>
Relief workers are speeding up repairs of the infrastructure
projects destroyed by the floods, and 32 medical and disease
prevention teams are also working in the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's civil affairs departments have provided 3.46 million
yuan (420,000 dollars) for parts of the flooded areas and six
groups are investigating flood damage.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the area are planting late rice seedlings, maize and
other crops.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province has received several million yuan in relief
funds from other provinces, overseas Chinese and foreigners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
