<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWII Japanese-style Caps Confiscated in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Caps modeled on Japanese soldiers'
headgear during World War II have been confiscated from markets in
Xiamen, southeast China's port city, and wearing of them is
banned, according to the "Yangcheng Evening News".
</P>
<P>
The city government had confiscated 28,751 of the caps sold in
street stalls and shops by the end of June. Some residents have
handed over caps they bought, voluntarily, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The army caps have been available throughout the city, since
early summer. Many of those seen wearing the caps, mainly
youngsters, said they just did it without thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
The caps aroused the strong resentment of local officials and
residents, many of whom said they thought they were an insult to
the nation's feelings.
</P>
<P>
"We should never lose national self-esteem and integrity no
matter how times changes," a citizen told the newspaper,
explaining his feelings.
</P>
<P>
Like other parts of China, Xiamen was invaded by Japanese
troops during WW II. Some 35 million Chinese were killed or
wounded during the eight-year war of resistance against Japan
(1937-1945), according to an official document of the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The paper did not say whether the cap producer, Yongguan Cap
Company of Xiamen, has been warned, but it said that city
officials have ordered departments to "strictly investigate the
matter".
</P>
<P>
In north China's Tianjin City, the Japanese Tianjin Koei
Company has been closed because it produced a computer game
featuring battles between Japan and Allied troops during WWII,
according to a "China Daily" report today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials in charge of investigation said that the
Japanese firm, whose software contained images of war-era planes,
ships, and war criminal Hideki Tojo, violates China's Provision on
Electronics Publication. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Harassment of Civilian Vehicles Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Defense officials in the east of
Sierra Leone today reported increased "rebel harassment of
civilians and commercial vehicles" traveling along the highway
linking Kenema and Kailahun districts.
</P>
<P>
A senior military officer in Kenema confirmed in a telephone
interview that five commercial vehicles were "ransacked" by
rebels within the past four days.
</P>
<P>
Media reports from the area said passengers were "stripped
naked and told to go home without their belongings."
</P>
<P>
According to one Lebanese businessman whose goods were among
those looted, a total of 80 bags of rice, 15 bags of onions,10
boxes of tomatoes were looted.
</P>
<P>
The four incidents have "created a great fear in the business
community in the area," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to one journalist, Ndonbah Junction between Hangha
village and Mano Junction is the main point of rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Information Minister Goerge Banda Thomas speaking
at a press conference late Wednesday denied media accusations
that the South African mercenary group, Executive Outcomes was
involved in diamond mining in Kono, in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Outcomes has a security contract with the Sierra
Leone government and is fighting alongside government troops in
the rebel war.
</P>
<P>
"It is the responsibility of the government to protect the
state and it was the EO that helped ward off the rebels when they
were within range of the capital last year," Banda Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
Director of Mines Andrew Belewa also denied issuing any
license to the EO to mine diamonds, he said about two members of
the EO have resigned their jobs with the group, left the country
and have come back with a number of investors but the government
has not yet given clearance to them to undertake mining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
