<HEADLINE> Wales Looks for Role in 2006 World Cup Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of Wales
(FAW) Thursday said that they were hoping to talk to their English
counterparts about the possibility of playing a role in the bid
for the 2006 World Cup, according to reports from Cardiff.
</P>
<P>
FAW president Brian Fear said: "Wales could never hope to stage
a World Cup on our own, we just haven't got the grounds. But we
would love to be involved in one and I'm sure the Scots would
too."
</P>
<P>
"With Japan and Korea staging the 2002 World Cup jointly it
has set a precedent and I would have thought it would be a great
idea to get the whole of the United Kingdom involved," Fear
added.
</P>
<P>
The English launched their bid after the highly succesful Euro
96 competition in June and received immediate support from the
government.
</P>
<P>
However, the government's Heritage Department has also granted
46 million pounds (71.48 million U.S. dollars) towards the
modernisation of the National Stadium in Cardiff.
</P>
<P>
A Heritage Department spokesman said: "We wouldn't want to
pre-empt the F.A. on how they formulate their bid, but we would
acknowledge that there are top quality facilities in all parts
of the UK and believe it would be possible to put together a
four-country bid."  
</P>
</TEXT>
