<HEADLINE> Pakistani Government Seeks to Control Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto said here today that her government is making all efforts
to push back the tide of high population growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a message issued on the World Population Day today, Bhutto
said that the current high rate of population growth is thwarting
the efforts to achieve sustainable development in social and
economic fields.
</P>
<P>
"The population of Pakistan increased so fast that from the
rank of 14th in 1950 ..." she said, adding, "Pakistan is now the
seventh most populous country of the world."
</P>
<P>
"The current rate of growth of 2.8 percent per year could
double the population of 134 million in 25 years," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has launched a population welfare
program and family planning services in the country but is facing
difficulties in implementing the schemes particularly in rural
areas, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, the government will continue its efforts, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistani President Farooq Leghari also sent a
message on the day, calling for mass awareness of the threat of
high population growth in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
