<HEADLINE> New Head of Sydney Olympian Organiser Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 11 (Xinhua/OANA) -- The Sydney Organising
Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) appointed its new chief
operating officer today.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG Chief Executive Mal Hemmerling announced in Sydney today
that Gerry Moriarty, a top-ranking telecommunications executive,
would be SOCOG's second in command.
</P>
<P>
The position of chief operating officer in SOCOG was newly
created. Moriarty will be the first person assuming the position
in September.
</P>
<P>
He will be responsible for logistical services, technology,
games services and facilities.
</P>
<P>
Moriarty is presently the chief executive officer of Telstra
Multimedia under the government-owned telecommunications company
Telstra.
</P>
<P>
He joined Telstra in July 1993 as managing director of Network
Products before being appointed chief executive officer of Telstra
Multimedia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
He spent 26 years in the radio, television and
telecommunications industries. Before he joined Telstra, he used
to worked with the Broadcasting Corporation of New Zealand and the
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) Television New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Hemmerling said that Moriarty was selected from a "strong field
of applicants."
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted that Telstra agreed to release someone of
the calibre of Mr Moriarty for the term of the project (September
1996-2001)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former SOCOG President Gary Pemberton resigned from the
position because of business reasons in March.
</P>
<P>
John Iliffe, Chairman of the retail giant Woolworths, succeeded
Pemberton as the President.
</P>
<P>
Since SOCOG was established on November 12, 1993, six of the 13
members of its board have been replaced. Among those who quitted
is Kerry Packer, the richest man in Australia.
</P>
<P>
One of the major issues faced by SOCOG is the budget
blowout. In the latest development, the Australian Olympic
Committee (AOC) announced Wednesday that its agreement with the
New South Wales state government on the distribution of the Games
revenue was in jeopardy temporarily. The two parties disagreed on
several clauses of the final version of the agreement, which have
to be handed to the International Olympic Committee on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
