<HEADLINE> Five Millions Books Ready to Reach Children in Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Five million books were printed
and its first batch sent today from Beijing to children in China's
relatively poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Donated by the Hope Project, the books are are part of an
effort to help poor children make productive use of their summer
vacation, which in China begins in mid-July and lasts about six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Hope Project, which helps young dropouts return
to school, established storage "stack rooms" for books designated
for poor children. More than 150 publishing houses across the
country recommended over 2,500 books for selection by stack room
editors.
</P>
<P>
Publishing houses also turned over the books' copyrights to the
Hope Project, and over 700 writers whose works had been selected
by the stack room editors also donated their copyrights.
</P>
<P>
"Bing Xin" Stack Room, named for a well-known Chinese
children's writer, was donated to Laiyuan Hope Primary School in
north China's Hebei Province, the first beneficiary of the Hope
Project.
</P>
<P>
The Hope Project, sponsored by the Communist Youth League of
China (CYLC), was initiated in 1989, and had collected donations
worth nearly 700 million yuan by the end of last year. The project
has funded the establishment of 2,074 Hope primary schools and
enabled more than 1.25 million dropouts to return to the
classroom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Women from Rural Areas Form Families in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Many marriages between rural
women and men from urban Shanghai are doomed to failure, experts
in China have warned.
</P>
<P>
The women laborers flocking to China's biggest city have
becomes wives of Shanghai men, but sociologists said the situation
has potential problems.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in districts linking urban areas
and the city's outskirts, over ten percent of the marriages have
been formed between urban male residents and female laborers from
outside Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In Luwan District, 988 couples registered their marriage during
the first five months of the year, and 188 couples, about 19
percent of the total, were formed by husbands from Shanghai and
wives from other places.
</P>
<P>
Government officials in the district said such marriages
appeared in the early 1990s, and the number soared around 1994,
when the municipality quickened its urban construction.
</P>
<P>
The females, most of whom came from rural areas in Anhui,
Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, ventured to the China metropolis
to find work as housemaids or factory workers.
</P>
<P>
Their long stay in the city gave a life style resembling that
of urban women, and many even speak fluent Shanghai dialect.
</P>
<P>
Their husbands had found it hard to find wives in the city
because of poor family backgrounds, poor schooling, disease or
physical defects. But the hard-working rural women show much
respect for the old -- answering the marriage dreams of many
men 'left on the shelf'.
</P>
<P>
The rural women appear to have been accepted and cared by many
urban residents. Some districts even opened classes to help
improve their work prospects.
</P>
<P>
However, sociologists think that many of these marriages will
face a series of social problems.
</P>
<P>
Some rural women married in a rush in order to seek a home and
shelter in a city foreign to them. As a result, their marriages
lack solid bases, and many may end in divorce in the future.
</P>
<P>
It is a conventional practice in China that the residences of
children follow their mothers, but the disparity between urban and
rural life remains large.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that the children of such marriages are
very young, but they will still face difficulties when the are old
enough to attend nurseries or schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
