<HEADLINE> South Koreans Demand Compensation From U.S. Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Villagers living near a
U.S. military base in South Korea plan to file a suit against the
state demanding compensation for the damage they have sustained
from the noise coming from the firing range of the base.
</P>
<P>
Involved in the move are about 3,500 people from 730 households
located near the firing range of the 7th United States Air Force
in Hwasong County of Kyonggi province.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for demanding 12,500 dollars per person in
compensation for a total of 43.8 million dollars for mental and
physical damage they claim have sustained from the noise caused by
bombing and shooting exercises at the firing range since it was
established in 1968.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time for villagers to ask for
compensation from the state in connection with the "military
noise" in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
"In the initial stage, we plan to file a 1.25
million-U.S.-dollar compensation suit before the end of this month
and another suit asking for the rest of the expected compensation
will be filed later after we evaluate developments," said Chon
Man-kyu, chairman of the committee pushing for compensation.
</P>
<P>
The villagers also plan to submit a petition to the National
Assembly urging compensation for the noise damage and seek the
formation of a consultative body on the matter with the Defense
Ministry, American forces and villagers represented.
</P>
<P>
Some 37,000 American troops are currently stationed in South
Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
