<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Lift Subsidies on Bread </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has disclosed a detailed plan
to lift subsidies on bread on grounds that that the price hike
will not affect citizens' standard of living.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information Marwan Muasher said citizens will
receive annual payments to offset the increase in the price of
bread, according to today's English-language daily Jordan
Times.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will put a mechanism to distribute
subsidies to citizens, who will be divided into three categories.
</P>
<P>
The first group includes Jordanians with National Aid Fund
coupons, whose number totals 200 to 250 persons. This group
will be given bread for free, he said.
</P>
<P>
The second group comprises Jordanians working in public and
army sectors, who have Ministry of Supply coupons and who will
be given 15 dinars (21 U.S. dollars) annually to help them buy
bread at the expected new price of 250 fils (35 U.S. cents)
per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The third group, which includes Jordanians with high
income who are not entitled to Ministry of Supply coupons,
will also be re-funded for the extra cost they pay for
bread.
</P>
<P>
"Every Jordanian will receive 25.26 dinars (about 35
dollars) every year to offset differences between the current
and new prices of bread to ensure that none will be affected," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"By providing the annual subsidy to Jordanians, the government
will be paying a total of 64 million dinars (about 89.6
million dollars) from the treasury," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the move will save the country 53 million dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
Recent press reports said that the government has been
subsidizing bread by 112 million dollars; fodder by 112 million
dollars; sugar, powdered milk and rice by 56 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the government is expected to
announce the decision of lifting subsidies on bread soon,
despite severe criticism from the opposition parties and the
public who had threatened to overthrow the government if the
subsidies are lifted.
</P>
<P>
Lifting of the subsidies on bread is the most important step
in the reform program the government launched in 1991 with the
cooperation of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is also a major step the government has yet to take
so as to reduce the government's budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters that maintaining subsidy will mean
a budget deficit which the IMF has warned the Kingdom of
developing.
</P>
<P>
The last price increase of bread in 1989 under the request
of the IMF triggered riots throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Faces Trade Deficit with NAFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand faces a trade deficit
with the three North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
countries for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months this year, Thailand recorded a trade
deficit totaling 5.75 billion baht (230 million US dollars) with
the NAFTA countries, which are the US, Canada and Mexico, a
Business Economics Department source said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total loss, 4.277 billion baht (171.1 million dollars),
or 74.4 percent, went to the US, 17.1 percent to Canada, and 8.5
percent to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The source said Thailand is likely to face a trade deficit with
the three countries for the first time this year since NAFTA came
into being in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In the said four months, two-way trade between Thailand and the
three countries grew 11.5 percent, with Thai exports increasing
only 1 percent and imports growing 23.6 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States represents the biggest market for Thailand
with a 93.4 percent share among the NAFTA countries. The Canadian
market share was 5.4 percent, while the Mexican share was 1.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Thai share in the US market dropped to 1.53
percent from the 1.55 percent recorded in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The source attributed this year's loss to four main factors --
declining Thai domestic input, especially in frozen shrimp
production, fierce competition in markets for jewelry and shoes,
a lack of raw materials such as those needed for the canned
seafood category, and the protectionist measures against canned
tuna and frozen shrimp.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months this year, a sharp drop in export
value was registered for jewelry, frozen shrimp, shoes, rubber,
radios, television sets and parts, canned fruit, video players,
raw coffee and stereos and parts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
