</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The ultra-rightwing party of National Front led by
Jean-Marie Le Pen imposes censorship in libraries of
Orange. Jacques Bompard, a member of the National Front who was
elected mayor of Orange in August 1995, has cleaned the city's
library of all books considered being "cosmopolitan" or "harmful
to good morals".
</P>
<P>
-- One week after the reelection of Boris Yeltsin as Russian
President, fightings resumed in Chechnya, whose civilians were
bombed by Russian aircraft in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
-- French prisons are overfilled with 58,616 prisoners
occupying 49,552 cells, according to a report by Gilbert Azibert,
director of prison system administration, who described the
situation as the worst in France since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Interior Minister Jean-Louis Debre said that despite
opposition from the Catholic Church, the government will continue
to carry out the policy of expelling illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
He said 6,072 foreigners without proper papers have been
expelled so far this year, a 25 percent increase over that of the
same period last year. Some Malians and Moroccans were expelled on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Russia's State Duma (the lower house of parliament) voted
Wednesday not to return Germany's cultural treasure that Soviet
troops seized in 1945. In protest, German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel said Germany would not send any extra financial aid to
Russia in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Soviet troops seized 200,000 objects of art, two million rare
books and three kilometers of archives from Germany at the end of
World War II. Germany has asked Russia to return the treasures.
</P>
</TEXT>
