<HEADLINE> First Children Library in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A newly-opened children's
library in Guangzhou has served more than one million young
readers in the capital city of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The library was established on the site where a former
drugstore was constructed in 1930s by Hu Wenhu, a late Hong Kong
businessman. Last year, the land was donated to the local
government by Hu's daughter to be used as the city's first
children's library.
</P>
<P>
The city government spent more than seven million yuan to build
the modern, computerized facility.
</P>
<P>
In the library's collection are more than 200,000 books, 400
magazines, 70 newspapers and audio-visual materials, according to
library curator Lai Jiamei. Five reading-rooms have a total of
over 400 seats.
</P>
<P>
The library opened on June 1, International Children's Day.
</P>
