<HEADLINE> Mi-17 Helicopters Used in Operations against PKK in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has been using the
Russian-made Mi-17 helicopters for transportation and medical
evacuations in operations against the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) in the southeast of the country, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Daily News said the helicopters are being used as transport
and hospital carriers in support of the massive state operations
aimed to wipe out the PKK rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, it reported quoted a Turkish military official as
saying that the 65-million-dollar purchase of 19 Mi-17s in 1995
was criticized by defense experts and the media in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that lack of spare parts and maintenance
support for the helicopters were the main problems, adding that
the helicopters stood idle here for months until sufficient spare
parts were flown in and the helicopters could be put into service
in the southeast of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 12-year guerrilla war for
self-rule in southeastern Turkey since August 1984.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 people, including PKK rebels, civilians and
soldiers of the Turkish security forces, have been killed in
the armed clashes between the PKK and the security forces.
</P>
<P>
The 65-million-dollar agreement signed by Turkey and Russia in
1995 for the purchase of 19 Mi-17 helicopters was the result of a Russian
proposal to cover its nearly 200-million-dollar debt to Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
