<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most of Chinese Workers Care About Income, Advanced Studies, Health: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese workers are paying more
attention to earning more income, receiving more education, and
maintaining their health, according to results of a national
survey.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 desire of more than 65 percent of 1,153 workers
questioned at state-owned, collectively-owned and township
enterprises, and also in foreign-funded joint ventures throughout
the country, was to make more income.
</P>
<P>
About 35 percent of them said that they were more concerned
about pursuing advanced studies and upgrading knowledge, and 31
percent cared more about personal health and individual medical
care.
</P>
<P>
"The results reflected the change of Chinese workers' thoughts
and demands in the current market-economy period," said Liu
Xiayang, the survey organizer, and deputy director of the Public
Opinion Research Institute of the People's University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"More Chinese people have come to understand the principle of
`survival of the fittest,' since social competition is getting
fierce," explained Liu. "And they are beginning to pay closer
attention to the need for self existence and development."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has been promoting reforms in the
state-owned enterprises, including the reform of the
"cradle-to-grave" welfare system.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the burdens of improving incomes, housing, medical care
and in-service training have gradually transferred from the
shoulder of governments and enterprises to that of workers
themselves," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"That is why so many surveyed workers showed solicitude for
those matters," he said.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed workers also were concerned about housing,
their children's education, and the protection of their personal
rights and interest, and to some extent, interpersonal
relationships with their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
It found that workers at the state-owned and collectively-owned
enterprises paid more attention to income, housing and medical
care than those employed by township enterprises and joint
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprise workers named on-the-job training as the
most important thing they wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that workers from various age groups
responded differently to many of the survey questions.
</P>
<P>
The first life choice for workers under 25 was education, while
workers older than 56 first considered health and medical care.
</P>
<P>
Those in the 26-55 age group cared more about income, housing,
education of children and mental health, the survey showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers to Consider Charges for Using </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Environment
</P>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from 18 members of the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) today agreed to encourage
new approaches like monetary charges for the use of environment to
promote sustainable development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Environment Secretary Victor Ramos, who chairs the
two-day APEC ministerial meeting on sustainable development, told
reporters that the ministers have expressed support for the
proposal submitted by the APEC senior officials' meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministers agreed to encourage new approaches to
sustainable development. Among these new approaches are the use of
market-based instruments like monetary charges for the use of the
environment, information sharing and the application of
participatory management and capacity building.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of sustainable cities, the ministers also
indicated support for the promotion of exchanges of scientific and
technical knowledge, the sharing of experiences and technologies
between and among economies.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also backed the promotion of dialogue among
public and private sectors and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the ministers have emphasized the need to integrate
environmental rehabilitation with economic development. For this
purpose, promotion of clean production and clean technology within
the region is a major item on the agenda of the two-day meeting
which will try to adopt the "APEC cleaner production strategy".
 
</P>
</TEXT>
