<HEADLINE> Foreigners to Observe Nigerian T.U. Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming delegates's
conference of the Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC) will be witnessed
by foreign observers to show that the government has no hidden
agenda on the democratization of trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The arrangements are being finalized to ensure that notable
foreign labor leaders should attend the conference, r. j. a.
Hobobo, NLC National Secretary, said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, it was initially decided to invite
organizations such as the International Labor Organization (ILC),
the Organization of African Trade Union Unity and perhaps the
International Confederation of Free Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
''However, at the ILC conference which ended in Geneva on June
20, many African countries, especially the French-speaking ones
indicated interest to attend,'' Hobobo said.
</P>
<P>
Hobobo said that the exact date of the conference would soon
be announced and the secretariat was fully prepared to carry it
out successfully.
</P>
<P>
The executive of NLC was dissolved in August 1994 following a
strike action. Consequently, a sole administrator, Ason Bur, was
appointed by the government but later replaced by Alhaji Ahmed
Gusau, who has restructured the 41 industrial unions to 29.
</P>
<P>
A delegates' conference earlier fixed for May 28 to 31 in the
capital of Abuja was aborted because of disagreement among labor
leaders arising from decree 4 of 1996 that banned general
secretaries and other employees of industrial unions from
contesting elections.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of industrial unions who have now mended fences have
asked the Head of State General Sani Abacha to amend the decree
to enable all trade unionists, whether elected or employed, to
contest election, but is not yet clear if this request will be
met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
