<HEADLINE> Electronic Linkage To Enliven HK Futures Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Futures products on the New York
Mercantile Exchange (NYMEX) is expected to be traded in Hong Kong
at the end of this year when an electronic system links the two
financial hubs.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Futures Exchange Ltd. (HKFE) has planned to
introduce an electronic screen-based trading system from the
NYMEX, and the installment will soon start in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the NYMEX have met with their members in
Hong Kong and members of the HKFE, providing them with details of
the system called "NYMEX ACCESS". Trading in NYMEX products will
begin within 1996 with the approval of the Hong Kong Securities
and Futures Commission.
</P>
<P>
The NYMEX has a dozen of member companies in Hong Kong while
the HKFE has 130 members. All these companies show their
enthusiasm to the linkage program.
</P>
<P>
Under the linkage agreement, the two futures exchanges will
jointly develop new futures contracts for the Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
The NYMEX is the world's largest physical commodity bourse,
dealing in energy products such as crude oil and refined petroleum
products, and precious metal product including gold, silver and
copper. The HKFE mainly offers futures contracts on Hang Seng
Index, three blue-chip stocks and rolling forex of Mark and Yen.
</P>
</TEXT>
