<HEADLINE> There's Monkey Business During Class at Chinese School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- If there's monkey business during
the lessons at a school in China it's hardly surprising.
</P>
<P>
Lazy students at Zhoushuizi Primary School in Dalian are
suddenly attentive. And there are feathers flying in the
schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
It is all because the school has opened its very own
zoo. Pupils can share their lessons with monkeys, sheep, hedgehogs
and a variety of birds.
</P>
<P>
The school, in Ganjingzi District of Dalian City in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, has so far 'enrolled' more than 300
small animals and birds. The idea is to give the pupils easier
access to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Each class at the school take turns feeding the animals and
birds, and cleaning their mini-zoo.
</P>
<P>
"A few students who used to be particularly lazy are now
interested in their work," said a teacher of the school.
</P>
<P>
"Contacts with animals will not only benefit pupils' physical
and psychological health, but also improve their sense of
environmental protection."
</P>
<P>
Soon the school is to bring in 200 pigeons to fly around the
school playground.
</P>
<P>
Lessons in nature and wildlife have taken on a new meaning for
the pupils at Zhoushuizi school, who have welcomed their
new 'classmates' with open arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
