<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 08:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Discover New Genetic Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Scientists of Tel Aviv
University have discovered a rare new genetic disease and
identified the defective gene that causes it, the Jerusalem Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Named TA-24 in honor of the university, the disease --
which makes patients extremely sensitive to sunlight -- has been
recognized by the scientific community.
</P>
<P>
Professor Hanoch Slor of the Sackler School of Medicine's
human genetics department, headed a team that discovered the
disorder, which involves faulty ability to repair the DNA in
the genes (or transcription-coupled DNA repair).
</P>
<P>
For several years, Slor's team conducted research on a
related disease, xeroderma pigmentosum (XP), in which patients are
extremely sensitive to ultraviolet light. It causes the
irreversible appearance of pigments in the skin and skin
growths.
</P>
<P>
Discovered in 1968, XP involves the inability of the body to
repair damage to the DNA in all the cell's genes. It can be
detected during the early stages of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Since most chemotherapy drugs used for treating cancer work
by linkage with the DNA and preventing the cell from
dividing, XP patients are 1,000 times as sensitive to UV
rays and to chemotherapy drugs. Chemotherapy can cause them
serious harm and even kill them.
</P>
<P>
Since XP patients suffer from tumors, doctors must be very
careful not to give them chemotherapy drugs that act like UV
light on their DNA.
</P>
<P>
For the past 14 years, Slor and his colleagues have been
treating a youngster who is hypersensitive to UV light. He was
suspected of being a member of one of the 30 Israeli families
suffering XP. A few minutes of exposure during midday caused
serious him burns -- but very little pigmentation characteristic
of XP was produced.
</P>
<P>
Using a technique developed in England to test DNA repair,
they found that his general DNA repair was normal, but that
only specific ("active") genes were unable to repair their DNA.
The body's parents -- cousins of Iranian origin -- show no
sensitivity to the sun.
</P>
<P>
Since XP causes permanent pigmentation of the skin, and the
little pigmentation that the youngster developed quickly faded
away, Slor concluded that he was suffering from a different,
previously unidentified disease.
</P>
<P>
It is not known how many people in the world suffer
from TA-24, but the importance of the discovery, says Slor, is
the characterization of the process responsible for DNA repair
in active genes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
