<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Readjusts Building Materials Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China has mapped out an ambitious
program to readjust its fledging building materials industry by
focusing on new building materials and products that will bring in
high economic returns.
</P>
<P>
The country's building materials industry has expanded rapidly,
showing a yearly growth rate of more than ten percent in cement,
glass and sanitary ceramics production, said Qiao Longde,
vice-chairman of the State Administration of Building Materials
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Qiao recently spoke at a press conference for China Building
Materials '96, which will be held at the China World Trade Center
un November.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country's building materials industry brought in
260 billion yuan in output value, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice chairman, China invested 17 billion yuan
in the construction of 41 large and medium-sized projects; 25 have
been put into production.
</P>
<P>
The effort led to an increase of more than 10 million tons of
high-quality cement, 3.6 million cases of float glass and 20,000
tons of high-quality refractory materials. Three production bases
that produce building materials and sanitary ceramics products --
Tangshan, Boshan and Foshan -- have been established.
</P>
<P>
He said 2.5 billion US dollars of overseas capital was
channeled into the building materials industry, an amount five
times the total used in the past ten years. More than 100 joint
ventures were set up using 100 million US dollars in overseas
capital in Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The official said the building materials sector made 2.2
billion US dollars from exports in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Although China's building materials industry claims a fairly
large output for its number of enterprises, Qiao pointed out the
sector has also been plagued by high energy consumption, low
productivity, poor economic returns, enormous waste in resources
and serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
As a result, China will implement its readjustment program in
three steps: First, in the next five years, China will concentrate
on improving the quality of building materials products and new
materials using extensive technological innovation and eliminating
outdated procedures.
</P>
<P>
Second, between 2000 and 2010, China will focus on the
modernization of production of items such as plate glass and
sanitary ceramics, mostly in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Finally, China will promote the development of new building
materials, non-metallic minerals, and inorganic non-metalic new
materials in order to build a modern, internationally competitive
building materials industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
