<HEADLINE> Thai Woman Accused of Abusing Laotian Child Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A Thai woman employer has been
arrested here on charges of committing brutal acts against two
Laotian teenage girls, including branding one of them with a hot
iron, the Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Wipaporn Tangtraporn, 39, owner of a glove factory in Bangkok,
was charged with assault and inflicting injury to others and
employing child labors.
</P>
<P>
The two girls, 14-year-old Suay and 11-year-old Noy, said their
employer used a hot iron and boiling water to keep them awake and
made them swallow insecticide when they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post today carried a picture showing two large burn
marks on Suay's back just under the shoulder blades. One of the
marks is a triangular scar about 15 centimeters (six inches) long.
</P>
<P>
Police said Suay told them that her employer placed the hot
iron on her back to punish her for forgetting to unplug it.
</P>
<P>
Noy, who also suffered skin burns, said her employer poured
boiling water over her to prevent her from falling asleep in work,
which often last for 22 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
The two girls said they were never paid in their four months
working at the factory although they had been promised a monthly
salary of 1,000 baht and 800 baht (40 and 32 US dollars)
respectively.
</P>
<P>
They are now in hospital after being rescued by police in a
raid on the glove factory earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The factory owner is also facing a charge of employing foreign
labor without authorization, which carries a maximum penalty of
three years in jail and/or a fine of 60,000 baht (2,400 US
dollars), the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
