<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Farmers Say Good-Bye to Old Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Modern towns and centrally-located
villages are springing up in east China's Jiangsu province as
older villages vanish with the changing patterns of life.
</P>
<P>
According to the local government, natural villages, with their
irrational layout and lack of facilities, can no longer meet the
demands of farmers and rural economic development.
</P>
<P>
To improve farmers' standard of living, the local government
came up with a plan by the end of June to speed up construction of
towns and central villages, whereby 40 percent of the farmers will
move to rationally designed, functional towns and central villages
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for the construction of 1,986 new towns in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Jiangdu City, in the center of the province is one example,
with its 4,627 natural villages that will merged into 288 central
villages by 2010.
</P>
<P>
With improved infrastructure facilities, the towns and the
central villages will make life more convenient for farmers, while
helping protect soil resources and poor farmers by merging rich
villages and poor ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
