<HEADLINE> Iran Refutes Netanyahu's Charges for Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
refuted Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's allegation
that Iran is acquiring atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister Hussein Sheikholeslam said
"Iran's doors are open to international inspectors and there are
no restrictions as our nuclear facilities are for peaceful
endeavors."
</P>
<P>
In a report carried in today's English-language daily
Tehran Times, he said that international inspectors from the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) visited Iran several
times and confirmed that Iran plans to use atomic energy for
peaceful purposes only.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official also denounced Netanyahu for his recent
hardline statements, saying that "he violated all international
laws and norms. Netanyahu is the one who reneged on all
commitments made by his predecessor."
</P>
<P>
"Look at his cabinet ... it's cabinet of warriors and
criminals such as Ariel Sharon, who was responsible for the
massacre of the Palestinians in Sabra and Shatila," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "members of the Netanyahu cabinet believe in a
greater Israel and they are expansionists."
</P>
<P>
On U.S.-Israeli collaboration, Sheikholeslam said, "they both
dance to the same tune and hail each other." 
</P>
</TEXT>
