<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an's Ambition to Be Trade Center  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, capital city of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province has drawn up plans to march forward into
the next century as an important trade and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
The city, home of the famous terracotta warriors, has set
itself the task of becoming an important center in central and
western China over the next 10 or 15 years.
</P>
<P>
It wants to regain some of its former glory when it enjoyed the
status as imperial capital of China and starting point of the
Great Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to cater to the country's overall plan to shift its
emphasis on economic expansion to the west.
</P>
<P>
The country's reform and opening-up drive, which was initiated
in 1979, brought an economic boom in some of its coastal
areas. However, many of China's hinterlands are still economically
less-advantaged.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an's city authorities say that they will not miss the
opportunity to regain Xi'an's status as a commercial and trade hub
in history.
</P>
<P>
The city, once called Chang'an in ancient times, was China's
old capital over 12 dynasties. It was known as a trade center of
China, even of the world, during those glory days of old.
</P>
<P>
It aroused great concern that in Han Dynasty (206 b.c - 220
a.d.), China opened the Silk Road, linking up with central and
west Asia, India and the European continent, with Chang'an as the
starting point of the road.
</P>
<P>
History only tells the past. Though Xi'an today has become a
world-renowned tourist attraction for its typical ancient Chinese
culture, it shows no signs at all of being a flourishing trade
center.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, Chinese President Jiang Zemin wrote an
inscription for the city, which reads, "To build Xi'an into a
socialist open city, depending on science, technology, tourism,
commerce, and trade."
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort to achieve this goal, Xi'an city is
projected to build five to ten large enterprises in charge of
commodity distribution, which are expected to have a very sharp
competitive edge in both overseas and domestic markets, and nearly
70,000 commercial and trade services over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, the city's total retail volume is expected to
reach 40 billion yuan by the year 2000, and 130 billion yuan by
2010, growing by 20 percent a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
