<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an's Ambition to Be Trade Center  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"After years of development, Xi'an city now has many advantages
to boost commerce and trade," said Cui Lintao, secretary of the
city CPC committee.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1995), the city's retail
sales rose by an annual average of 21.43 percent, reaching 18
billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
The city's 1995 retail volume ranked first among seven
provincial capitals -- Xi'an, Lanzhou, Urumqi, Yinchuan, Xining,
Taiyuan, and Zhengzhou, in central and western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Last year Xi'an built 82,000 commercial service networks at a
total cost of 1.03 billion yuan. About 430,000 people were
reportedly involved in commercial business.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an now operates nearly 50 air routes, ranking third in China
and first in central and western China.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an has a telephone switchboard of 300,000 lines. Three
national optic fiber cables have been built, and another three are
under construction.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an ranks in third place in terms of comprehensive scientific
and technological strengths in China, only after Beijing and
Shanghai, with 345,000 experts in various fields. The number of
college students, out of every 10,000 head of population in the
city is the highest in China.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an boasts approximately 600 laboratories for different
research purposes, including 24 state key labs. It takes a lead in
China in developing and making research on aeronautics,
astronautics, machinery, power equipment, optic instruments and
meters.
</P>
<P>
And Xi'an is a foreign exchange and securities hub in northwest
China, with more than 1,800 banks and other financial
institutions. Xi'an's residents are reported to have a total of 30
billion yuan in cash and deposits.
</P>
<P>
"The key is to turn the resources into economic advantages."
Cui said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
