<HEADLINE> Tumen River Development in Different Stages (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have come up
with a theory explaining the development of the Tumen River
region, which includes parts of China, Russia, and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, using different spaces and stages.
</P>
<P>
Chen Cai and Yuan Shuren, both are doctoral advisors at the
Research Center on Northeast Asia at Northeast China Normal
University, have been doing research on "Local Characteristics of
the Tumen River Zone and its Time and Space Development Modes."
</P>
<P>
The research is part of China's major social science programs,
and took Chen, Yuan and colleagues three years to complete.
</P>
<P>
They say that in the region's development, there are three
geological zones described as concentric circles. The inner one
includes China, Russia, and the DPRK. The second circle includes
Japan, the Republic of Korea, and Mongolia, countries that have
direct relations with the development. The outer circle includes
the United States, UN organizations, and several districts that
can help and can benefit from development of the region.
</P>
<P>
Chen and other scholars predict that, because the region lacks
a strong economic foundation and because the transformation from
cold-war confrontation to all-round co-operation will take time,
development will be divided into three stages:
</P>
<P>
From 1996 to 2000, China, Russia, and the DPRK will develop the
region separately, while co-operating tentatively. They will
intensify construction work on highways, railways,
telecommunications, ports, and other infrastructure in their own
territory to build a foundation for future co-operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
