<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Increases Steadily in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of tourists visiting
Uganda has increased steadily since 1986 when the country's
current government came to power.
</P>
<P>
A report issued here today by Uganda Tourist Board (UTB) said
last year tourists visiting Uganda were 193,000 who spent 90
billion Shillings (about 90 million U.S. Dollars) in the country.
</P>
<P>
This, the report said, compared to 32,790 tourists with an
expenditure of 16,067,000 Dollars in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The highest increment since 1986 was in 1995, the report said,
adding that the number of tourists increased by 34 percent (from
144,085 in 1994 to 193,000 in 1995) and their expenditure
increased by 25 percent (from 72 million Dollars in 1994 to 90
million Dollars in 1995).
</P>
<P>
On reasons for the boom, the report said it is, among others,
the prevailing peace and stability across the country since 1986
that attracts tourists to visit Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Eco-tourism, a different style of tourism in the country is
another reason for Uganda to attract tourists, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Each of the three east African countries have something unique
to themselves. Tanzania is the best for wildlife, Kenya has the
best beaches, and Uganda's forests are the best south of Sahara.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's position is particularly well-placed, because all its
new 10 national parks are forest oriented, the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, it said, Uganda-based tourism operators are now a
threat to the Kenya-based ones. Even the Tanzanians are, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
