<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Families Becoming More Democratic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey has shown that
China's families are becoming more democratic as the relations
between husbands and wives, parents and children become more equal.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the males and more than half of the females
surveyed expressed disagreement with the idea that "men should pay
more attention to society while women pay more to the family".
</P>
<P>
In Shenzhen, in south China's Guangdong Province, a life of
young couples managing their own properties is now in vogue, and
love as a factor young people consider when setting up a family is
common.
</P>
<P>
In a survey of 1,441 families of farmers in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, 64.5 percent said that "love plays the most
important part in family life."
</P>
<P>
Those couples who think that love no longer exists are now more
likely to divorce rather than endure a loveless marriage.
</P>
<P>
The family democracy is also mirrored in the relationship
between parents and children, the survey showed. Parents are no
longer the domineering authority and the views of children are
given more attention, the survey showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
