<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bedouin Tribe in Jerusalem Faces Eviction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A Bedouin tribe on the
outskirts of Jerusalem is caught between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), according to a Jerusalem
Post report today.
</P>
<P>
Earth movers this week began working three meters from one
of six Jahalin Bedouin encampments in the path of Ma'aleh
Adomim, northeast of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli High Court imposed an August 28 deadline on
the tribe to move to another site allocated to it, but
members of the tribe said they are torn between the Israeli
order and PNA orders.
</P>
<P>
The new site is closer to Abu Dis, an area which had
already been handed over to the PNA, and PNA officials said
the land to which the tribe is being relocated is private
land belonging to residents of the town.
</P>
<P>
Although some 100 Jahalin families already live there, they
have no permanent right of residence, while the 49 others
(about 400 people) ordered to move refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
They said that they fear they will be victimized by the
PNA as collaborators if they move with an Israeli assurance
that their relocation is permanent, and they would not move
if it only means they can be shifted again.
</P>
<P>
The Jahalin fled the Negev in southern Israel in 1950 and
settled in the Judean desert under Jordanian rule. It is situated
on way to Jericho and safe from the encroachment of Israel's
developing society on the Negev Bedouin.
</P>
<P>
In 1967, they found themselves under Israeli rule again,
and in the most rapidly developing settlement area of all,
furthermore, the land where they lived was declared state land
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the civil administration began talking to them and in
1993, the year that witnessed the signing of the Oslo accord
between Israel and the Palestinians, they were offered alternative
sites.
</P>
<P>
They then chose Abu Dis-Kedar, to which water and power
line as well as a road were extended, but now the Jahalin
also have to contend with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Radio reported after a meeting between Jahalin
representatives and PNA President Yasser Arafat that Arafat
rejected "attempts at occupation" by the Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dis is also the home of Palestinian Council Chairman
Ahmed Qeria, apparently one of those with land claims in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The council appointed a seven-member committee to help the
Jahalin stand fast against settlement expansion, arguing it is
their land, they are Palestinians, and they may not be
forcibly moved under international law.
</P>
<P>
While 45 years of relative quiet came to an end this
week with bulldozers, trucks, and earth movers encircling camps,
sheep pens, and even individual tents and huts, the Jahalin
said they are not nomads.
</P>
<P>
Israel is offering them the right to build homes in the
new site, if they can find the money, but the PNA will
not tolerate that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
