<HEADLINE> Scorpion Venom Found to Be Effective in Treating Tumors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found
that an extract of scorpion venom has proven effective in treating
tumors in humans, according to a report in Shanghai's "Wen Hui
Daily" today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Henan Medical Science University in central
China discovered that a polypeptide extracted from scorpion venom
had a strong analgesic effect and could improve the human immune
system.
</P>
<P>
Clinical tests showed the polypeptide was also effective in
relieving pain in cancer patients, and had few side effects,
according to Prof. Kong Tianhan, director of a research center of
biological toxin at the university.
</P>
<P>
Kong and his colleagues have conducted tests on medical
applications of scorpion venom for eight years, the paper said,
and "The finding marks a breakthrough in the field of scorpion
venom used for treating tumor, and has attracted the attention of
scholars both at home and abroad." 
</P>
</TEXT>
