<HEADLINE> Shanxi's Mt. Wutai International Tourism Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Mt. Wutai, the highest peak in
north China and home of one of China's greatest Buddhist shrines,
will be the site of the 7th Mt. Wutai International Tourism Month,
from July 25 to August 25.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 40 temples and ancient buildings on the
3,058-meter-high mountain, which has been venerated by Buddhists
as a sacred site since 58 A.D., and with Emei Mountain in Sichuan,
Jiuhua Mountain in Anhui, and Putuo Mountain in Zhejiang, is one
of Buddhism's most important sites.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wangcheng, a Wutai County official, said that tourists
can visit temples, ancient buildings, forest parks and watch
performances of Buddhist rites.
</P>
<P>
A trade fair will also be held during tourism month, with over
100 new products of electronics, light industry, building
materials, chemical, food, and clothing to be shown.
</P>
<P>
Mt. Wutai was listed in 1982 among China's highest group of
state-level scenic spots and historical sites. Wutai County has
put some 200 million yuan (24 million U.S. dollars) into building
the tourist area since then.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 Chinese and overseas tourists visit Mt. Wutai
each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
