<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New-type Oasis Agriculture Road Could Mean Wealth For West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A new type of agriculture may
become the royal road to prosperity for arid, desert regions in
western China, and help narrow the economic gap between eastern
and western parts of the country, according to a senior scientist.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture is doing especially well in the Hexi Corridor
in Gansu Province, Vice-Chairman of the China Association for
Science and Technology Liu Shu said at a symposium on investment
in middle and western regions.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, the "new-type" agriculture means that, under
vulnerable, arid, and water-short conditions, new artificial
control measures are used, with a "more light, less water
consumption, new technology and high output" model.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who is a researcher in prevention and treatment of desert
disasters, says the model includes use of plastic film mulching
technology in large areas, the use of greenhouses to increase
production, and drip irrigation and other water-saving irrigation
measures.
</P>
<P>
The new-type oasis agriculture was pioneered by a prominent
scientist, Qian Xuesen, a decade ago, and will markedly improve
natural resource use, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Liu cited the example of Israel, which has per capita fresh
water resources of less than 300 cubic m, but five percent of the
gross national product and 6.56 percent of the national foreign
currency earnings come from only 3.5 percent of the national labor
resources.
</P>
<P>
Israeli technology is not mysterious, and what they have
achieved can also be achieved in west China, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He proposed making the new-type oasis agriculture a popular
mode of agriculture in the region and called on governments at all
levels in the region to perfect the green house technique, mainly
by improving the durability and intake of light, accelerating the
use of value-added plants and animals fit for cultivation in green
houses, and improving management to avoid possible mold diseases
and "white pollution" caused by waste plastic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Coastal People Urged to Flee Hurricane in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one million coastal
residents and tourists have been urged to evacuate as Hurricane
Bertha churns on towards the east coast of the United States with
165 kph winds.
</P>
<P>
About 500,000 people were ordered to evacuate six Florida
counties on Wednesday. Another 50,000 were urged to get off
Hatteras and Ocracoke islands on North Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
Officials also urged the evacuation of parts of two South
Carolina counties with 380,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
In Georgia, more than 1,000 Olympic officials were being
evacuated from the yachting venue on the coast and were moving
competition yachts inland. They also took down tents and removed
technology, computers and data bases from the site.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
(NASA) moved its Florida space shuttle Atlantis off its launch pad
to the shelter of a hangar. And the Navy ordered ships out to sea
to avoid being battered against the docks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton cancelled a flight to Florida on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bertha, growing in the Caribbean, arrived in the Bahamas on
Tuesday. The winds increased to 180 kph early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Weather Service has issued a hurricane watch
for the coast of Carolina and parts of Georgia and Virginia,
fearing that Bertha would approach the region on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At 8 p.m. eastern standard time on Wednesday, the hurricane was
centered about 120 kilometers northeast of Great Abaco in the
Bahamas, and about 320 kilometers east of the Florida coast. It
was moving northwest at about 24 kph, the Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, meteorologists had predicted the storm would take a
gradual right turn during the day and its strongest wind and rain
would move on a course parallel to the U.S Atlantic Coast. But it
has been moving northwesterly toward Florida.
</P>
<P>
The Hurricane brushed by Puerto Rico on Monday, then the Turks
and Caicos Islands on Tuesday. Three people were killed in
storm-related accidents in Puerto Rico and one in the Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
Also in Puerto Rico on Monday, the Coast Guard reported that a
boat with as many as 42 people aboard was crippled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
