<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Chernomyrdin to Head New Russian Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Just days after Russian President
Boris Yeltsin's re-election, the question of the possible division
of portfolios in the new government has taken over the entire
post-election agenda.
</P>
<P>
As Yeltsin stated on Wednesday, Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin will stay on and is ordered to prepare the list of
the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Although Yeltsin said that he does not oppose including
representatives of different political parties in the new
government, Communist Party leaders are unlikely to get any
key posts in the new cabinet, analysts here believe.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no room for (Communist Party leader Gennady)
Zyuganov in the new cabinet," Vyacheslav Nikonov, former deputy
chief of Yeltsin's election campaign team, told the Moscow Tribune
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The idea of a coalition cabinet, advocated by the Communists,
will not work in Russia, which is a presidential, not
parliamentary, republic," Nikonov said.
</P>
<P>
Economics Minister Yevgeny Yasin, who is likely to keep his
post in the new cabinet, on Monday echoed Chernomyrdin's remarks
as he also rejected the Communists' participation in the new
government.
</P>
<P>
Yasin said that the new team -- which will not be announced
until the inauguration of Yeltsin next month for his second term
-- would be selected by Chernomyrdin and Alexander Lebed, the new
secretary of the powerful Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Lebed, drawn into the Kremlin inner circle ahead of last week's
runoff, has used his promotion to sound off on a variety of
issues, some of which fall directly under the prime minister's
remit.
</P>
<P>
Despite Lebed's demands for greater power, Yasin said the
retired general's rise would have a positive effect on the new
administration.
</P>
<P>
"We need a man of decisions," Yasin said, adding that Lebed
would play "a decisive role" in the fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
But Alexander Livshits, Yeltsin's chief economic adviser, said
that Lebed would not get the broad economic powers he has been
seeking. The full responsibility for economic policy would remain
with Chernomyrdin, he added.
</P>
<P>
In response, Lebed, who reiterated his earlier demands for a
key role in economic affairs, said he was looking for a deputy for
economic policy. "By the end of the summer or early fall an
economic and financial crisis is expected," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin met Yabloko's leader Grogory Yavlinsky
on Tuesday for consultations over possible new candidates for key
economic posts in the new government.
</P>
<P>
Though unlikely to enter the government himself, Yavlinsky has
been promoting Yabloko's Mikhail Zadornov -- who currently heads
the State Duma (lower house of parliament) Budget Committee -- to
get a high economic post in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Yavlinsky told reporters after his meeting with Chernomyrdin
that he plans to continue negotiations with the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
As for Russia's so-called power agencies -- which even
Chernomyrdin agrees to be Lebed's departments -- further
reshuffles among their leadership are unlikely, with only the
future of the Defense Ministry's top brass still unclear.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Yeltsin passed a decree making career KGB officer
Nikolai Kovalyov the fully-fledged director of the Federal
Security Service.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference on Wednesday, Yeltsin's top aide
Viktor Ilyushin noted that changes would also be made to the
president's entourage. He explained that the president would need
a new staff capable of working efficiently under the emerging
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In this context, Ilyushin said Yeltsin had met a group of his
aides on Monday on possible personnel changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
