<HEADLINE> Nepal Prepares Implementation of VAT Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is to
implement a new value added tax (NAT) from mid-April 1997 in order
to simplify the country's tax system and increase national revenue
collection.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed Wednesday by Finance Minister Ram Sharan Mahat
in his budget report for the 1996-97 fiscal year to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the existing sales tax and Excise Department
would be restructured into the Department of Value Added Tax in
the coming fiscal year starting from July 16.
</P>
<P>
However, the department will perform its current functions
relating to sales tax and excise until the VAT system is imposed,
according to Mahat.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements had been made to levy a single VAT rate of 15
percent to replace the prevailing two types of rates at present,
he said in the budget report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has decided to make some small
changes in the existing tax system by waiving sales tax for the
industries using domestic raw materials in their production and
raising excise duty on luxurious items like liquor and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the country would mobilize an additional
revenue of 1.8 billion rupees (30 million US dollars) through
these tax system improvements in the 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
