<HEADLINE> IDB Approves 134 Million Dollars for Health Sector Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) --The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of a 134 million U.S.
dollar loan to Trinidad and Tobago for its health sector reform.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to strengthen the health sector's
planning, management and policy-making capacity, separate the
provision of services from financing and regulatory
responsibilities, decentralize service delivery and management to
five autonomous regional health authorities as well as shift
public spending to priority uses and cost-effective solutions.
</P>
<P>
The program will be carried out over a period of seven years,
constituting the first phase of a sector reform program that is
set to take 10 to 15 years to complete.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 192 million dollars. In
addition to the IDB loan, local counterpart will contribute a
total of 58 million dollars. 
