<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Drops in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The crime rate has declined by 11.3
percent in Poland in the first half of this year, according to
the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in seven years that the crime rate has
reduced, Interior Minister Zbigniew Siemiatkowski told a news
conference today.
</P>
<P>
During the first 6 months, the police uncovered 400 major
criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
Out of 412,000 cases, 347,000 were criminal offences,
representing a 13.1 percent drop over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Homicide and car-stealing cases were 11.5 percent and 8 percent
down respectively while armed robberies and burglaries were 4
percent lower. Juvenile deliquencies also dropped by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the country will fight more
effectively against organized crimes in the second half of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
