<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Calls U.S. Sanctions Ridiculous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian Government minister
today described as ridiculous United States action in launching
sanctions against a Canadian company doing business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Sheritt International Corp. has been singled out by
the U.S. government as the first foreign company to be punished
under its Helms-Burton law.
</P>
<P>
Nine Sheritt executives and shareholders as well as their
spouses and children will be barred from the U.S. starting August
23, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) Television
reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto-based mining company was being punished because it
had a nickel mine in Cuba, the CBC said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Minister of International Trade, Art Eggleton,
said:"It is absolutely ridiculous for the United States to be
denying entry to people, particularly talking about children.
</P>
<P>
"Denying a couple of kids the opportunity to go to Disneyland
is not in any way related to their national security."
</P>
<P>
Despite the U.S. measure, Sheritt said today it had done
nothing illegal and it would continue to do business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Sheritt vice-president Patrice Best said:"It will not deter
people from doing business there. There are a great deal of
opportunities."
</P>
<P>
The American Helms-Burton law is aimed at curbing foreign
investment in Cuba by penalizing foreign companies doing business
in the Caribbean island country.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, senior executives and shareholders of companies
doing business with Cuba, can be denied entry to the United
States. U.S. citizens and companies can sue in U.S. courts
companies using properties confiscated by the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
Canada, along with Mexico and the European Union, has heavily
criticized the legislation.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Canada has decided to amend its own
legislation, which would allow Canadians to counter-sue in
Canadian courts to recover damages awarded by U.S. courts under
the Helms-Burton law.
</P>
<P>
Canada also vowed to fight the U.S. law under the North
American Free Trade Agreement, and in the World Trade
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
