<HEADLINE> Teenager Crimes Shoot up in The Czech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Teenager Crimes have shot up in the
Czech Republic since 1993 reaching nearly 140,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
A senior police officer told a press conference today that they
constituted 32.4 percent of all crimes -- meaning that one in
every three criminals was under the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
Shoplifting and thieving of car parts topped juvenile
law-breaking in the central European country, followed by homicide
and rape.
</P>
<P>
The officer blamed the mass inflow of western violence and blue
movie-videos and similar books into the Republic since 1989 as a major
factor causing the sharp increase of teenager crime.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic had forbidden all TV stations around the
country to broadcast violent and blue movie-videos before 10
p.m. Recently a station which violated the rule was fined 1.3
million Czech korunas (about 48,000 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
