<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia, Poland to Boost Economic, Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Croatia and Poland agreed today to
revitalize as soon as possible their trade ties which were
battered by the prolonged war in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks between Polish Prime
Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz and his visiting Croatian
counterpart, Zlatko Matesa, who arrived here on Tuesday on his
first visit.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that great efforts should be made by both sides to
restore the trade volume between the two countries to the level of
1989, two years before Croatia's declaration of independence from
the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
They both emphasized the importance of signing an accord on
free trade between the two countries as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the two countries had great potential in
maintaining broad cooperation in the economy, particularly in the
shipbuilding and power industries.
</P>
<P>
Matesa, whose two-day visit ended today, thanked Poland for its
efforts in resolving the nearly-four-years-long ethnic conflict in
the former Yugoslavia, including its dispatch of peacekeepers to
the area.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszewicz said Poland would support Croatia's bid to join the
Central European Free Trade Zone and would help in the country's
reconstruction work.
</P>
<P>
A bitter conflict broke out in Croatia in late 1991 when its
Serb minority revolted against the country's independence from the
former Yugoslavia. The war was stopped in early 1992 after the
United Nations stepped in and sent thousands of peacekeepers to
separate the warring sides.
</P>
<P>
But it erupted again in 1995 as Croatian troops staged a
massive offensive to recover territory held by the rebel
Serbs. Croatia retook most of the Serb-held land during the
offensive and the war officially ended last November when the
Dayton peace accord was signed.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord provides for a peaceful reintegration of the
last rebel Serb enclave into Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Set up Panel to Censor TV Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government will soon
set up a committee of experts to decide on the program contents to
be telecast on television, the National Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar here on Wednesday, Information and
Telecasting Minister C.M. Ibrahim said that such a body would be
useful in determining the software policy of the national
telecasters.
</P>
<P>
He said in the era of information revolution a careful study
has to be made about the future shape and role of media.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the press to be more responsive on national
issues and also ensure that honor and dignity of such high offices
like the president of India, prime minister, vice president, the
speaker and the leader of the opposition are maintained.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the official media, Ibrahim said they have the
responsibility of giving a right direction to the society.
</P>
</TEXT>
