<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Up 7.1 Percent in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports in the first
five months rose only 7.1 percent over the same period of last
year, much lower than the 18 percent target set for the year,
according to Commerce Minister Chucheep Harnsawat.
</P>
<P>
Based on Customs Department information, imports during the
said five months were worth 778.3 billion baht (31.13 billion US
dollars), up 12.16 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
With exports worth 586.8 billion baht (23.47 billion dollars),
the country's trade deficit for the five months was 191.5 billion
baht (7.66 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figures released by the commerce minister are at variance
with those published by the Central Bank, which reported an 11
percent export growth in the first five months this year.
</P>
<P>
Items with a higher export value this year included computers
and parts, integrated circuits, television sets and parts, air
conditioners, gems and jewelry, furniture, leather products,
canned seafood, rubber, sugar, rice, and tapioca pellet.
</P>
<P>
Among poor export earners were garments, shoes and parts,
plastic products and video recorders.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the less-than-expected export growth during the
first five months, the government has readjusted the export growth
target from 18 percent to 14 percent for this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
