<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today approved
a defense bill of 265.5 billion dollars by a 68-31 vote.
</P>
<P>
Differing from the version passed by the House of
Representatives in May, the Senate authorisation bill for
U.S. defense programs in 1997 requests preparations for a terror
chemical or biological weapons attack in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Both versions request 11.2 billion dollars more than President
Bill Clinton wants for the development of an anti-missile defense
and the purchase of ships and warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has threatened to veto the two bills passed by
Congress. But some Senators believe that the President and the
Congress would agree on a compromised defense budget of less than
265 billion dollars. 
</P>
