<HEADLINE> Two Speleologists Found Dead in Alps Caves of France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A British woman and a Hungarian man,
which were part of a six-member team of speleologists, were found
dead Wednesday in flooded caves in the Alps of southeastern
France, the AFP reported today.
</P>
<P>
Four other speleologists were rescued alive in the caves of
about 800 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
The names of the 31-year-old Briton and the 25-year-old
Hungarian confirmed dead have not been unidentified.
</P>
<P>
The six cavers, who were believed to be experienced and
well-equipped, were exploring the Berger caves Sunday and being
trapped in the most dangerous parts of the caves after heavy rains
caused rising water there, said the French news agency.
</P>
<P>
Police and rescue teams were trying to bring the survivors and
the two bodies to surface, but the task may take several hours,
the local authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The Berger caves are among the deepest in the world and are
located at an altitude of 1,460 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
