<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Drops in Australia in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Australia's unemployment rate
dropped to 8.3 percent on a seasonally adjusted basis in June from
8.5 percent in May, according to figures released here today by
the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
</P>
<P>
The country's total employment figure rose by 8,700, or 0.1
percent, to 8.33 million in June from 8.32 million in May, the ABS
said.
</P>
<P>
The figures boosted the local financial market immediately
after their release this morning. The Australian dollar
strengthened to 79.75 US cents from 79.70 US cents and the futures
market in Sydney also went higher.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate in June fell back to the level of one year ago
while a less proportion of the population remained in the labor
force than in June last year.
</P>
<P>
The participation rate, or the proportion of working-age people
who either have or are seeking a job, remained basically unchanged
from the previous month at 63.4 percent in June. But it was lower
than the 63.8 percent one year ago.
</P>
<P>
The ABS figures were in accordance with the Treasury's latest
economy forecast, which predicted that the unemployment rate would
fall further in the latter half of the year but that the inflation
rate would be capped.
</P>
<P>
However, the ABS figures ran contradictory to the statistics
released today by the Australian Department of Social Security,
which showed that 2,500 more people joined the jobless group
receiving government doles in June.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that in the general picture, Australia's
labor market showed signs of a steady recovery. According to ABS
figures, the country's employment improved by 3,300 in trend terms
in June over May, while the unemployment rate stabilized at 8.6
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
