<HEADLINE> Beijing Municipal Academic Degrees Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A municipal academic degrees
committee that will promote work toward academic degrees and
graduate education, has been set up in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Academic Degrees Committee is under the
leadership of the municipal government and the Academic Degrees
Committee of the State Council, for vocational work.
</P>
<P>
The committee is responsible for the planning of academic
degree work and awarding of academic degrees at the bachelor's,
master's, and doctoral level.
</P>
<P>
The committee is also in charge of local laws, regulations and
management of academic degree work in the Beijing area, according
to today's "Beijing Daily".
</P>
<P>
Beijing has 115 schools that can award doctor's degrees, 30 of
which are institutes of higher learning. There are 233 schools
that can award master's degrees, 48 of which are schools of higher
learning. Of 67 local colleges and universities, 60 have the right
to award bachelor's degrees.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Beijing had 8,500 students studying for
doctor's degrees, accounting for one-fourth of the country's
total. The number of graduate students exceeded 24,000, some
one-fifth of the country's total, and undergraduates, 146,000,
accounting to nine percent of the country's total. 
</P>
