<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Withdraws Open Shipping Market Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has decided to withdraw
offers to open up its shipping markets to foreign companies under
the World Trade Organization (WTO), a business economics
department source said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai decision was made following the deadlock of WTO
negotiations on the liberalization of maritime transport.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the offers would not mean a freeze on future
foreign access to Thai shipping markets, which include both
on-shore handling and sea transport, Bangkok Post today quotes the
source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Neither does it mean that Thailand is no longer prepared to
convert its liberalization measures into commitment under the WTO.
</P>
<P>
It means that basic WTO principles, such as the absence of
discrimination between countries, would not have to be applied to
the shipping sector, the Post said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai offers would have committed Thailand to allow foreign
companies access to international passenger and goods services,
international towing, and various support services including
freight forwarding, but with some exceptions.
</P>
<P>
A last-ditch attempt to rescue the world shipping talks failed
last month when the U.S. refused to submit an offer even though 24
of the 42 countries and regions participating in the talks had
improved their liberalization offers.
</P>
<P>
It was decided in late June in Geneva that new negotiations
would not be held until the year 2000, meaning that a shipping
agreement might not be reached before 2005.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
