<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges Reinforced Crime-fighting in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin is
urging a strengthening fight against crime in Moscow and its
region.
</P>
<P>
In a decree submitted by his national security adviser
Alexander Lebed and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, Yeltsin put Lebed,
who is also the secretary of the Security Council, in charge of a
new drive to fight crime in Moscow and the region, the Itar-TASS
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
More effort to check crime in Russia was part of both Yeltsin's
and Lebed's presidential election platforms early this
year. Lebed, an ex-paratroop general, joined Yeltsin's team after
he came third in the first round of voting last month.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Luzhkov and Interior Minister had criticized the
Interior Affairs Bureau of the Moscow municipality, describing its
work as "unsatisfactory."
</P>
<P>
Police registered 46,671 cases of crime in Moscow in the first
half of the year, with wilful murders and rapes rising by 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
Mercenary killings rose by 69 percent, bringing the number to
27, from 16 in the same period last year. 
</P>
