<HEADLINE> Transportation Cooperatives Join in Strike in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Some transportation cooperatives
in Nicaragua today joined in the general strike launched by the
transportation operators on Tuesday demanding an indefinite tax
exemption.
</P>
<P>
They accused the government of being intransigent because Labor
Minister Francisco Rosales had rebuked as "electoral rhetoric as
well as absurd" a draft legislation which proposed an indefinite
tax exemption for transportation cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
The minister insisted that the cooperatives be granted tax
exemptions for short periods only but never on an indefinite basis.
</P>
<P>
The strike, being staged by freight and passenger
transportation operators, was later joined by urban and
inter-urban mass transportation cooperatives from Masaya, Granada,
Matagalpa, Carazo and other places.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly was sieged on Wednesday by dozens of
transportation vehicles including minivans that came to reinforce
the sit-in taxi operators there.
</P>
<P>
The freight and mass transportation cooperatives in Managua had
asked the government to extend the present seven-year tax
exemption to an indefinite period. They vowed to continue the
strike until their demand is met.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth national transportation strike since
President Violeta Chamorro took office in April, 1990. Several
deaths and huge property damage were reported during the previous
labor unrests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
