<HEADLINE> World Bank Helping Yunnan Fight Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has started the seventh World-Bank-sponsored public health project
in China, which is to help local people in poverty-stricken areas
get protection from disease.
</P>
<P>
The project involves about 7.5 million US dollars' worth of
interest-free loans and will last for five years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, the province has cooperated with the United Nations
and the World Bank to increase the number of inoculations for
children against measles, diphtheria, pertussis, and
poliomyelitis. The rate of incidence of these four diseases has
dropped by 93.64 percent from 1983.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank loans will mainly be used to improve medical
equipment and train medical staff members.
</P>
<P>
The province has also started an anti-AIDS campaign,
establishing six quarantine stations along its 4060-km border with
neighbouring countries, to halt the increasing number of deaths
caused by AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
