<HEADLINE> China's largest Flood Warning System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's largest and most advanced
flood warning system went into operation in east China's Fujian
Province on Wednesday, after a year of trial operation.
</P>
<P>
The system is one of five major flood control projects in
Fujian, and has 98 stations covering an area of 30,000 sq. km in
the Minjiang River basin.
</P>
<P>
During the trial operation, the system succeeded in predicting
the worst flood of the past two decades in Pucheng County in
northern Fujian and the largest flood in Jian'ou City of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The system is the result of a Sino-Japanese joint
venture. Japan provided 2.3 billion yen in aid while the Chinese
side was responsible for equipment installation and other jobs.
</P>
