<HEADLINE> China To Increase Port Capacity by 300 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China plans to increase the
capacity of major sea and river ports by 300 million tons over the
next five years, with stress to be placed on energy, raw
materials, and foreign trade cargo terminals, according to a
high-ranking transportation official.
</P>
<P>
Li Juchang, a vice minister of communications, told reporters
that the country expects to build over 200 berths, each exceeding
1,000 tons in capacity, which will mainly be built in large
coastal ports considered vital to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"Priority will be given to constructing coal, major raw
materials, and container terminals", he said, also explaining that
the ministry will make an effort to help some regions build an
international navigation center, with Shanghai as the hub and
Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces as the spokes.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, over the past five years, 283 berths have
been built in major ports along the coast, with an increased
capacity of 120 million tons.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the combined capacity of major sea and
river ports reached 1.08 billion tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
