<HEADLINE> China's Steel Production Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China produced a total of 51.4
million tons of steel and 48.65 million tons of pig-iron during
the first half of this year, up 1.77 million tons and 2.25 million
tons respectively over the same period in 1995, reported today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of the Metallurgical Industry
showed that during the January-May period, 106 large and
medium-sized iron and steel enterprises received a sales income of
99.85 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars), down six percent from
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Their combined pretax profits, standing at 8.5 billion yuan
(1.02 billion US dollars), declined 31.8 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the ministry attributed the situation to the
rising prices of coal, electricity, gas and transportation, the
sluggish market and falling steel prices.
</P>
<P>
During the January-May period, exports of billet and rolled
steel were only 2.59 million tons , down 31.8 percent from last
year. Exports of pig-iron also decreased.  
</P>
</TEXT>
