<HEADLINE> Mexico Makes Progress in Population Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is making progress in
its family planning program, says a high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
Jose Gomez de Leon, secretary-general of the National Council
on Population, said today that 67 percent of married Mexican women
now used contraceptives. And each woman of childbearing age had an
average of 2.7 children as against four a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the first progress report for the National
Population Program 1995-2000, Gomez de Leon said more than 70
percent of married couples in urban areas planned their families,
and 50 percent in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The country had a population of 93 million with a controllable
population growth rate of two percent a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
But more efforts were to be made in family planning as there
were enormous difference in birth rates for different regions in
the country, Jose Gomez de Leon said. 
</P>
