<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continued Slump in China's Materials Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Supplies of materials in China
continue to surpass demand, causing prices to continue to drop,
according to a weekly release by the China Materials Information
Center.
</P>
<P>
The market slump is mainly the result of decreasing exports and
increasing imports, and slow growth in consumer demand, analysts
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, the prices of 39 major materials rose, while
60 dropped and 75 remained unchanged, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
Steel products continued their sluggish trend, with prices of
15 items up a bit, 18 lower, and six unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The national average for 0.5mm cold-rolled ordinary thin plate
was 5,598 yuan (674 US dollars) per ton, a decline of 20 yuan; and
that of 38kg heavy track was 4,115 yuan per ton, a drop of 18 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The prices of nonferrous products also continued to decline by
a large margin, with copper dropping by 314 yuan per ton to 25,683
yuan and aluminium by 44 yuan to 16,568 yuan, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Prices of most chemical products, including rubber, plastic
materials, organic, and inorganic products, continued to drop in
some areas, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
