<HEADLINE> Hinterland to Get Shot in the Arm for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's still-underdeveloped
inland will get favorable policies in an ongoing effort to
encourage overseas investment there, according to today's "China
Daily".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Buhe, vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, as saying that
priority will be given to the fields of agriculture, mineral
resources exploration, raw materials, infrastructure construction
and labor-intensive industries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, 18 provinces and autonomous regions in
China's central and western regions had approved over 40,000
overseas-funded enterprises, accounting for 17 percent of the
total in the country, and involving a total of 13 billion US
dollars of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The area and population of China's central and western regions
take up 85.5 percent and 62 percent of the country's total,
respectively, yet their gross domestic product accounts for only
44.9 percent of the country's total. 
</P>
