<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The largest Tang dynasty stone
coffin ever found in China has been discovered in a secret burial
chamber here in Xi'an, the ancient capital of several Chinese
dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Two other chambers had been looted over centuries by grave
robbers - but they missed the hidden tomb, according local
archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
More than 140 exquisite tri-colored pottery figurines, and the
large carved stone coffin from the Tang Dynasty (618-907) have
been found intact in the robbed tomb.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is located in Gaoling county, 20 km north of Xi'an,
capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province. It belonged to Li
Hui, minister of justice of the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Close to the Weihe River, way leading to the tomb and wall
paintings had been washed away by water. The front and back
chambers of the tomb, and a passage connecting the chambers were
empty because of repeated robberies over the past few centuries.
</P>
<P>
To the surprise of archaeologists who went to the tomb
recently, a hidden chamber was found close to the the front and
back chambers.
</P>
<P>
A passage, 11.6 meters to the west from the pass and turning
north for another 20 meters, led to the mystery chamber.
</P>
<P>
A four-meter long, three-meter wide and two-meter high outer
coffin was found in the chamber. Designs of ladies, officials, and
flowers were carved on the stone coffin.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the stone coffin is the largest Tang Dynasty
(618-907) coffin ever found in the country.
</P>
<P>
Beside the coffin were some 160 burial articles, including 139
tri-color pottery figurines.
</P>
<P>
From the gravestone,the archaeologists established that the
tomb belonged to Li Hui, Minister of Justice of the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, the emperor of Tang once
said that he, and the people around him, would be unhappy if they
could not see Li Hui for one day.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that perhaps that is why the tomb structure of Li's
tomb is so special, and some of the burial articles were able to
survive attacks by grave robbers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
