<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cultural Relics Found in Deserts in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A Cliff painting depicting an
ancient nomadic tribe living in 18 tents has been discovered on a
mountain in the southeastern part of China's second largest desert.
</P>
<P>
The painting is one of some 4,000 cliff paintings found in the
Badain Jaran Desert in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, a great number of cultural relics have also
been found in the sandy areas in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition to several sites of cliff paintings dating back to
the Neolithic, Bronze and Iron Ages, archaeologists have found
wooden slips from the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD), military
facilities from the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), paper money from the
Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368), and some 3,000 pieces of documents
written in Han, Tibetan, Mongolian, Arabian and Western Xia
languages.
</P>
<P>
Western Xia Dynasty (1038-1227), was set up among a nomadic
tribe in northwest China, with present-day Yinchuan in neighboring
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region as its capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Give Bulgaria Big Aid to Boost Nuclear Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) agreed today
to give Bulgaria 7 million ECU (9 million U.S. dollars) in loan to
help boost the safety at the country's nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to finance the work of Bulgaria's
Committee on Peaceful Use of Atomic Energy and cooperation between
the Bulgarian Kozlodui nuclear power station and its counterparts
in west European countries.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum was signed here by Atanas Paparizov, Bulgaria's
minister in charge of trade and foreign economic cooperation, and
O'Salivan, EU ambassador to Sofia.
</P>
<P>
O'Salivan told reporters that the new loan approved for
Bulgaria was part of the so-called Phare Program, under which
Bulgaria has received nearly 1 billion dollars in loans from the
EU over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Kozlodui, which was built in northwestern Bulgaria 22 years ago
with the help of the former Soviet Union, is the country's sole
nuclear power plant but has the largest annual generating capacity
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have expressed deep concern over the safety
at the ageing Kozlodui and other nuclear power plants in eastern
Europe and the former Soviet republics, most of which were built
with Soviet technology now widely considered outdated by current
international standards.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria has shut down some of the generating sets in Kozlodui
for safety tests in recent months with the help of the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Concerned Over Aging Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government is
worried about the the rapidly aging population of the country
which has swollen by 700 percent in 26 years.
</P>
<P>
There are now seven million elders in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the 48th annual meeting of the Brazilian Society for
Progress and Science, in Sao Paulo, the government sounded alarm
that the aged, Brazilians over 65 years old, will number 9 million
at the end of the century and 16 million by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
The largest number will be women, who number 100 to every 83
men.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was told that Brazil, with the world's sixth
largest population of 153 million, would approach same ratio of
aged as in developed European countries by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that the increasing aged population was
occuring despite a slowing-down in the overall population growth rate
which fell from 3 percent a year between 1940-60 to 1.9 percent in
1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
