<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Presidential Candidates Likely to Face </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The key presidential candidates in
Nicaragua will have to face a run-off after they fail to net
enough votes in the October 20 general elections, says a poll.
</P>
<P>
According to the electoral law, a second round of votes will be
held on November 24 or December 1 if none of the candidates obtain
at least 45 percent of the valid votes during the first round.
</P>
<P>
The Cid-Gallup poll, carried out between June 26-July 2 and
published on Wednesday by the "La Tribuna" newspaper, showed that
if the elections were held today, Liberal Alliance presidential
candidate Arnoldo Aleman, the former mayor of Managua, would rank
first with only 36 percent of the votes in the electoral
preference.
</P>
<P>
Former Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega of the Sandinista
National Liberation Front (FSLN in Spanish) would come second with
26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the former survey, Aleman advanced 3 percentage
points in the electoral preference while Ortega gained 5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that the increase in the votes for the
two strongest candidates was due to the failure of several parties
to form an alliance as a third force.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Supreme Electoral Council disqualified
presidential candidates Antonio Lacayo of the National Project,
Eden Pastora of the Democratic Action Party and Alvaro Robelo of
the Nicaraguan Alliance which was dissolved at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Analysts pointed out that Aleman and Ortega would not see any
further improvement in voters preference since the former was seen
as a continuation of the Somocista government and the latter as a
return to the former Sandinista regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
