<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Borders Could Be Reopen Under Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu indicated today that he would like to reopen Israel's
West Bank and Gaza borders to let Palestinians resume work in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But he told the ABC television program "Good Morning America"
in an interview that the reopening can take place only when he is
satisfied that Palestinian leaders are doing all they can do to
prevent attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The border closure was implemented most recently earlier this
year by the Israeli Labor government after a spate of guerrilla
bombings, which has prevented thousands of Palestinians from
going to Israel to work.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe in unnecessary hardships for the Palestinian
population.... What I would do is, if the Palestinian Authority
keeps its commitments on a permanent basis, on a serious basis,
to prevent terrorist attacks against us from their domains, then
I will certainly ease up on the closure," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the ABC program that he would like to undergird the
peace process with economic prosperity for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"My policy toward the Palestinians would be one of economic
cooperation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
