<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Share prices at the New York
Stock Exchange managed to move higher today at the prompt of more
buyers which made blue chips to finish higher.
</P>
<P>
But weak technology shares and uncertainty about the future of
the economy kept the broader market mixed.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, which had been down nearly 50
points, turned around in the last hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed 21.79 points higher at 5,603.65, but declining
issues still outnumbered advancers on the New York Stock Exchange
by a margin of 4-to-3. The total volume increased to 421.31
million shares from 379.19 million Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index gained 0.18 to 351.75. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 1.31 to 656.06.
</P>
<P>
But, the technology-rich Nasdaq composite index lost 15.44
points to 1,138.15 while the American Stock Exchange market value
index fell 4.86 to 561.81.
</P>
<P>
Today's early declines were triggered by Motorola, the big
semiconductor and telecommunications company, which reported
Tuesday evening that its second-quarter profits were far short of
analyst estimates, falling 32 percent. Motorola partly blamed
slack demand for semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
The earnings shortfall erased any optimism generated by the
semiconductor industry's monthly book-to-bill report for June,
which showed the third straight increase in the ratio between new
orders and previous orders that were billed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
