<HEADLINE> Mitterrand Angered by "Rainbow Warrior" Bombing: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Late French President Francois
Mitterrand once described the sinking of Rainbow Warrior by
French secret agents in July 1985 as "an intolerable crime" and
"an unforgivable stupidity."
</P>
<P>
According to a previously unknown interview he gave to a
journalist in August 1995, French secret agents sank on July 10,
1985 Rainbow Warrior, a vessel of the Green Peace movement,
outside the port of Auckland, New Zealand, to silence its protest
against French nuclear tests in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The interview Mitterrand had with journalist Patrick Amory at
his private residence in Latche, Landes, five months before his
death was published by the Paris-Match periodical in its Thursday
edition.
</P>
<P>
Mitterrand told Amory, "I have made two definite points, which
are the continuation of nuclear tests... and a request asking our
military not to intervene against our policy in the Pacific."
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes, the military act like idiot.... In some countries,
the supreme head of state knows every detail of the activities of
the secret services in their countries. I never love to enter such
details. Between being guilty and being imbecile, I have chosen
(the latter)," said Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
"I have never ordered the sinking of this boat or another....
The operation messed up things completely.... I will never take
any responsibility for what I think to be an intolerable crime and
an unforgivable stupidity at the same time," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
