<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Show Some Conciliation to Quell Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu today assured the U.S. Congress of the conciliatory side
of his foreign policies in an attempt to quell American fears that
his Likud government might slow the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Still, he made no specific proposals towards the final
settlement of the Middle East peace process in his 35-minute
Congress speech.
</P>
<P>
He told the members of Congress and diplomatic guests that
Israel's hand "is stretched out in peace for all who would grasp
in."
</P>
<P>
"Israel is ready to resume negotiations with the Palestinian
Authority on the implementation of our interim agreement.... We
are ready to engage Syria and Lebanon on meaningful negotiations.
We want a peace that will last," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, however, returned to his old theme that peace would
have to be based on "security for all," indicating the governing
Palestinian Authority in the West Bank and Gaza should prevent
attacks against Israel or peace could be halted and curbed.
</P>
<P>
"Peace means the absence of violence.... Peace without personal
safety is a contradiction in term," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu outlined three "pillars" that were necessary for
peace negotiations to proceed, which include "security" for Israel
against terrorist attack; "reciprocity" in which all disputes are
peacefully negotiated; and "democracy and human rights" in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Arab officials, responding to some of Netanyahu's comments,
said that peace will not be achieved without Israel returning all
occupied land. The secretary general of the Arab League and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa both urged Netanyahu to back
away from his tough policy pronouncements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
