<HEADLINE> Olympic Athletes Evacuate Hurricane-Threaterned Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 Olympic
athletes and staff members were being evacuated from the yachting
venue off the Georgia coast Wednesday as Hurricane Bertha was
heading for the southeastern coast of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Olympic officials said the athletes and staff members were
voluntarily leaving the marina at Wilmington Island, while other
residents of Georgia's barrier islands were poised for mandatory
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
About 35 sailboats, two keel boat classes and one catamaran
class, were being shipped to the main Olympic Marina site in
Savannah, The United Press International said, quoting Olympic
Games spokesman Marcus Hutchinson. About 165 smaller boats would
be left at the marina.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic athletes and staff members would hole up at the
Olympic Village and other accomodations in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
Hutchinson said that tents were being taken down and all
technology, computers, data bases are being removed from the site.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Bertha, growing up in the Caribbean region, arrived
Bahamas Tuesday. The winds increased to 115 mph early Wednesday,
making it a Category 3 storm capable of extensive damage.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Weather Service has issued a hurricane watch
for the coast of Carolina and part of Georgia, fearing that Bertha
would approch the region on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 residents and tourists on the barrier islands
in North Carolina began to evacuate Wednesday and emergency
officials in South Carolina also urged residents to leave coastal
Beaufort County.
</P>
<P>
The Hurricane brushed by Puerto Rico on Monday, then the Turks
and Caicos Tuesday. Three people were killed in storm-related
accidents in Puerto Rico and one in the Virgin Islands. Also in
Pueerto Rico, Coast Guard reported that a boat with as many as 42
people aboard was crippled Monday and passengers were jumping into
the water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
