<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Worries About Reorganization of Islamists' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- One year after the assassination of
an Algerian Islamist leader in Paris, France now fears a
reorganization of militant Islamists' networks and deployment of a
mujahidin force in Western Europe, said Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper reported in a leading story in its
Thursday's edition that through investigations on the
assassination of Sheikh Sahraoui on July 11, 1995, French police
have been able to put into light several international Islamists'
networks in France and other Western European countries.
</P>
<P>
The report said that French police have in the past year
dismantled several terrorist networks in the Paris area and in
Lille, and have put some of its members in jail.
</P>
<P>
Through questioning the Islamic militants, French security
forces have found one common background of these militants: all of
them have undergone trainings in camps in Pakistan and
Afghanistan, and many of them have fought alongside their Muslim
brothers in Bosnia, said the Le Monde report written by Erich
Inciyan.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Rachid Ramda, one of the leaders of Algeria's
extremist Islamic Army Group (GIA) who is being extradited to
France for terrorist activities from England, is one of the
pioneers in organizing a guerilla training camp in Peshawar at the
Pakistani-Afghan border.
</P>
<P>
He has also helped organize military training of Bosnian
Muslims in Bosnia, said the report, which said that "an Islamic
international" might already have come into existence.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic terrorists made a series of bombing attacks against
French targets, including the Lyon-Paris TGV bullet train in
August 1995, the Paris Metro subway train in October and the RER
long-distance train in Paris in July.
</P>
<P>
French police believe the attack was made by the militants to
revenge themselves on the killing of some hijackers by French
troops in December 1994 at the Marseille-Marignane international
airport, and the GIA is believed to be masterminding the attack.
</P>
<P>
"Today,the main channels of violent and radical Islamists
capable of threatening Western Europe pass through Pakistan and
Peshawar," Le Monde quoted a French magistrate specialized in
anti-terrorist affairs as saying.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1995, Judge Jean-Louis Bruguiere has been
heading an anti-terrorist organ called "Territory Watch" which is
responsible for investigating Islamic youths who return to France
from Pakistan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the result of some preliminary investigations made
by Bruguiere, some militants are now fighting in Afghanistan,
Algeria and Bosnia, but some of them have returned to Western
Europe and are waiting for "effective mobilization," said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Increasingly Being Appreciated in World, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Radoje
Kontic said today his country is increasingly being appreciated in
Europe and the world for its contribution to the reaching and
application of the peace agreement for Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Kontic positively assessed the attending
of a Yugoslav delegation he headed of the recent summit of central
and eastern European countries in Salzburg, Austria.
</P>
<P>
"The summit often said Yugoslavia was the guarantor of security
in the territory of southeastern Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is one of the three signatories of the Dayton
agreement which was signed in December last year to end the bloody
Bosnia civil war.
</P>
<P>
The summit also expressed expectations that in the coming
period Yugoslavia would play a key role in strengthening peace and
stability in the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that at the summit, attended by more
than 10 heads of state and government, many participants agreed
that it was important for them to support Yugoslavia's return into
international political and financial institutions and its
participation in sub-regional and regional cooperation in Europe,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has successfully resumed diplomatic relations with
many European countries, but it has not been readmitted into the
United Nations and many other international financial institutions
as the issue of rump Yugoslavia's status in the U.N. has not been
solved.
</P>
<P>
Kontic said the summit agreed that the sanctions should fully
be lifted, especially their "outer wall" since this could prevent
Yugoslavia from being a factor of peace and stability in the
Balkans, as the international community expects.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council suspended the
three-and-half-year-long sanctions against Yugoslavia in December
1995, but the total lift of the sanctions would not be realized
until elections in Bosnia were held in September as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to Kontic, businessmen from central and eastern
European countries, as well as those from the West, have shown
great interest in cooperation with Yugoslavia in the economic
field.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is much interested in normalizing relations with the
European Union "in a positive and pragmatic manner," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
