<HEADLINE> China-Hong Kong: Bridging Transition Seminar Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Commissioner to London
Sir David Ford said here today that Hong Kong will keep its
prosperity and development after Hong Kong's reversion from
Britain to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sir Ford made the remarks at a seminar entitled "China-Hong
Kong: Bridging The Transition" co-sponsored by the London Chamber
of Commerce and Industry and the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
Sir Ford said to keep Hong Kong's prosperity and continuous
development is the common desire of Britain and China. Having
dissolved the fear and misunderstanding about Hong Kong's
reversion from British to Chinese rule on July 1, 1997, Hong Kong
is attracting more and more people and investment from all over
the world, especially from America, Japan and European countries,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that by the time of Hong Kong's sovereignty
reversion from Britain to China, 75 billion U.S. dollars of
foreign reserves would be left there.
</P>
<P>
Sir Peter Cazalet, president of the China-Britain Trade Group,
also made a speech at the seminar. He stressed the great impact of
China's Ninth Five Year Plan on business, saying, "It will provide
enormous opportunities for the British investors."
</P>
<P>
Sino-British relations have turned friendly since Deputy Prime
Minister Heseltine visited China last May. Sir Cazalet believed
that "the momentum of the good relations between Britain and China
would exceed 1997."
</P>
<P>
More than 100 representatives from British government finance
and business circles attended the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
