<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers, Cargo Decline on Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Marine transportation on Lake
Victoria including passengers and cargo has declined since May
this year when a Tanzanian vessel capsized in the lake, killing
about 500 people.
</P>
<P>
Sources from Port Bell Pier near Kampala disclosed here today
that passenger and cargo traffic at the ports of Bell and Mwanza,
Tanzania, has drastically gone down.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the sources said, the number of passengers going
through Port Bell to Mwanza has dropped to zero.
</P>
<P>
The data from Port Bell Pier booking office indicate that
loose cargo including bicycles and spare parts, cotton seed cakes
and others from Mwanza to Port Bell averaged 50 tons per month
from the beginning of last year to May this year.
</P>
<P>
Loose cargo from Port Bell to Mwanza averaged 10 tons a month
during the same period, the data said, adding that the goods
included polythene bags, water melons, curry powder, passion
fruits, etc.
</P>
<P>
By June 20, the sources said, the last cargo to leave Port
Bell for Mwanza weighed an average of 18 tons.
</P>
<P>
From then on, there has been no more recording, due to the
catastrophe that hit marine transportation by the capsizing of
the Tanzanian vessel, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The numbers of passengers by marine transport on Lake Victoria
from Mwanza to Port Bell were 14,591 in l995 and the first five
months of l996 while those from Port Bell to Mwanza were 7,450 in
the same period, the sources said, adding the figure has now
dropped to zero. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
