<HEADLINE> Mostar Croats Threaten to Reject Elections Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the Bosnian Croats in
Mostar said today that Croats may reject results of the local
elections to protest against what they called "irregularities."
</P>
<P>
Mile Puljic, president of the Mostar branch of the Croatian
Democratic Union (HDZ) in Bosnia-Herzegovina, made the comment
following a request by the head of the city's election committee
to te EU administration to release the election results by degree.
</P>
<P>
Rauf Zaimovic, president of the election committee, asked the
EU administration to do so because releasing the results by the
committee itself has been blocked by its Croat members.
</P>
<P>
Croats have complained that there were "irregularities" in
oversea polling stations, where the majority of votes have gone to
the HDZ' main opponent, the Muslim-led Party of Democratic Action.
</P>
<P>
Puljic said, "The Croat side in Mostar would not accept results
of the local elections, should the EU administration in Mostar
publicize them by decree."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that such a move by the EU administration would lead
it into "the abyss of lawlessness" and increase "legal insecurity
in historic Bosnian elections scheduled for September." 
</P>
</TEXT>
