<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Banker Denies Whitewater Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- An Arkansas banker today denied
charges by Whitewater prosecutors that he diverted money from his
bank into Bill Clinton's campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
Herby Branscum Jr. told a federal court jury in Arkansas that
he had been a longtime Clinton supporter and had held numerous
state government positions. But he denied any quid pro quo, The
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Branscum said he was "absolutely not" guilty of any of the
charges contained in the indictment against him, in response to a
question by his lawyer, Dan Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
Branscum and Robert M. Hill, co-owners of Perry County Bank of
Perryville, Ark., are charged with conspiring to use their bank's
money to reimburse contributions by themselves and others to
Clinton and other Arkansas politicians.
</P>
<P>
They also are charged with concealing from the Internal Revenue
Service 52,500 dollars in cash withdrawals by the Clinton
campaign in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution presented evidence that Branscum was appointed
state highway commissioner in January 1991, five weeks after Hill
personally delivered some 15,000 dollars in campaign contributions
to Clinton. The prosecution has made no allegation that the
appointment was illegal.
</P>
<P>
Branscum said he had served in numerous state government
positions beginning with a 1974 appointment to the Arkansas Claims
Commission, which resolves claims against the state government.
</P>
<P>
Branscum became Arkansas Democratic chairman in 1976 and four
years later, Clinton appointed him to a second term on the
commission. In 1982, Clinton offered him the chairmanship of the
influential Arkansas Public Service Commission, which regulates
utilities, the banker testified. But he said he turned down the job
because he didn't want to give up his law practice.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's videotaped testimony for the trial was taken Sunday
at the White House, but Guthrie said he did not expect to play the
tape for the jury. Instead, jurors likely will see an edited
version of Clinton's taping, his second in a Whitewater-related
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
