<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Debt, Food Security Addressed by OAU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- African leaders today agreed to
take common stance on the issues of foreign debt and food
security in the two economic resolutions adopted by the 32nd
Summit of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The resolution on foreign debt announced the establishment of
an OAU contact group to coordinate among the member states over
the debt issue.
</P>
<P>
Africa's outstanding foreign debt rose by 18 billion US
Dollars to the historical high of 320 billion Dollars at the end
of 1995, accounting for 80 percent of Africa's total Gross
Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
That means if the debt burden is now shared equally among the
continent's estimated 680 million people, each African would have
to pay some 470 dollars, an amount which outstrips the average
per-capita annual income in the continent.
</P>
<P>
And during the recent years, 30 percent of Africa's foreign
currency income was used to service its foreign debt annually.
</P>
<P>
"It will continue to be the most serious single bottleneck of
Africa's economic breakthrough until there is a lasting solution
to the problem of Africa's debt," said OAU Secretary General
Salim A. Salim.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also highlighted the need for an effective
coordination, consultation and exchange of information and
experience among the African countries.
</P>
<P>
The resolution on food security said African leaders will take
a common stance in the forthcoming world food summit to protect
themselves from being further exploited by the unfair
international trade system.
</P>
<P>
In a world where 800 million people do not have adequate
access to food including 200 million children below the age of
five, Africa is the continent with the most serious problems.
</P>
<P>
"It is the only continent where agricultural production per
capita has been declining over the past 20 years," said the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Africa is faced this year with an additional 1.2 billion US
dollar bill for cereal imports, with its cereal stocks having
gone down to four percent below the security threshold, leading
to price increases of 40 to 50 percent, according to a report
released by the World Food Program. enditem

=07102149

=07102150
NNNN
05:50 05:50 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
