<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Set Can Be Linked to Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Families who now do not own
personal computers may soon use their TV to surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A new company in California has created a low-cost device to
enable TV sets to browse the Internet's World Wide Web, an idea
computer industry veterans have talked for months but not
realized.
</P>
<P>
WebTV Networks Inc., a Silicon Valley startup firm, planned to
demonstrate its device publicly for the first time today and
announce two powerful partners.
</P>
<P>
The potential market is huge: 100 million U.S. households have
TVs. Two-thirds of those don't have PCs and many of those can't
afford them, said a press report here today.
</P>
<P>
Sony Electronics Inc. and Philips Consumer Electronics Co. will
produce and sell machines based on WebTV's technology in
September, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a dozen companies, including large ones like Oracle
Corp. and IBM, have talked about lower-cost Internet access
devices in recent months.
</P>
<P>
WebTV Networks kept quiet, working with Sony and Philips for
months and building their trust by adhering to design deadlines.
</P>
<P>
WebTV's machine uses a phone line and universal remote control
to navigate the worldwide computer network. Logging on is as
simple as pushing a green button marked "Web" on the remote. A
wireless keyboard is optional.
</P>
<P>
Through clever programming, the company has overcome a major
hurdle by making Web pages look good on a TV screen, which portrays
images with less resolution than most computer monitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
