<HEADLINE> Britain Offers South Africa $93-Million Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
told visiting South African President Nelson Mandela here today
that the British government is to grant South Africa 60 million
pounds (93 million U.S. dollars) of aid.
</P>
<P>
Major, who made the pledge during a meeting with President
Mandela earlier today at the Downing Street, said that the aid was
targeted particularly at improving standards of education in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This pledge maintains the British government's support for the
political and economic transition of South Africa," Major said in
an official statement.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the aid will be used to promote development
in priority sectors agreed by the two governments: education, good
governance, health, rural development and the development of small
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"This new pledge of aid will continue work in the focus sectors
with particular emphasis on education," Major said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an area in which President Mandela takes a
particularly close interest and where he is determined to shift
the balance of resources to previously disadvantaged communities,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, President Mandela, who arrived here Tuesday for
his first state visit to Britain, received eight honorary degrees
at a presentation ceremony at the Buckingham Palace.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day visit, President Mandela is expected to
address a joint session of the British parliament and hold talks
with officials of the Bank of England and the Confederation of
British Industry to discuss further investment in South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
