<HEADLINE> Turkish Envoy on Helicopter Attack Incident in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A visiting Turkish envoy today said
he would try his best to persuade the Turkish government that a
technical commission should be formed to probe the recent Turkish
helicopter attack incident in an Iranian border area.
</P>
<P>
Erol Caker, Turkish deputy interior minister, said at a press
conference here following his three-day talks with Iranian
officials that Turkey has the Kurdish problem and there was an
exchange of fire between Turkish forces and rebels from the
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in the area along the Turkish-Iranian
border line.
</P>
<P>
The border incident killed six Iranians and wounded 15 others
in West Azarbaijan on June 26.
</P>
<P>
He said there was nothing wrong in the relations between
Turkey and Iran. The two neighbors enjoy stability in the common
border regions.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said at a meeting
with the Turkish official that the Turkish government should tell
its border officials to be more cautious and pay enough attention
to the Iranian border areas so as to prevent any incident which
might create doubts and suspicions.
</P>
<P>
He said such incidents are not in the interests of Turkey and
that preserving border security needs a mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said that it was part of Iran's decisive policies to
defend the security of the Islamic homeland and the safety of its
citizens.
</P>
<P>
But, Caker replied that his country follows the policy of
non-intervention in the internal affairs of other countries, and
voiced the willingness of his government in preserving good
neighborly relations with Iran and with other regional Moslem
countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Ankara-Tehran ties, he said that his country had
no intention to violate the Iranian airspace and if such incidents
had taken place they were outside the will and intention of the
Turkish government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
