<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Retains Chernomyrdin as PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia's re-elected President Boris
Yeltsin said today that he would retain Viktor Chernomyrdin as his
prime minister and promised to continue reforms during his new
term of four years in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a nationally televised address one day after he was
officially proclaimed re-elected, Yeltsin said he needs a strong
government to implement his program of actions up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Viktor Chernomyrdin must head the government,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, 58, has been a loyal Yeltsin ally since becoming
prime minister in December 1992.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he had already commissioned Chernomyrdin to
prepare proposals on a new composition and structure of the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, he went on to say, must be made up of
professionals and "competent and fresh people."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that he does not oppose the admission of
representatives of different political forces, including the
Communist Party, into the government.
</P>
<P>
"I do not oppose if representatives of these or those parties
would be in the government. There is only one provision: they
must forget about their political affiliation," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
He then promised to continue carrying out reforms, but added
that the nation's economic policy needs serious adjustment.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary "to revive production, to provide enterprises
with orders and people with work, to force growth of living
standards of each Russian family," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Yeltsin said he has already carried out a program of
actions against crime.
</P>
<P>
"The struggle against corruption in all echelons of power will
be the most important direction of my work," he said.
</P>
<P>
He promised his countrymen that during the next four years he
will do everything to make the country maintain stability and calm.
</P>
<P>
Having thanked the Russians for the trust they showed at the
presidential elections on June 16 and July 3, Yeltsin recognized
that elections have become "an important lesson" for him because
he was able to see his own drawbacks and mistakes in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
The Central Electoral Commission officially declared on Tuesday
Yeltsin's re-election as Russian president.
</P>
<P>
The commission said a total of 74.81 million people, or 68.89
percent of registered voters, took part in the second round of the
voting.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 40.2 million, or 53.82 percent, cast their ballots for
Yeltsin, and 30.21 million, or 40.31 percent, voted for his
communist challenger Gennady Zyuganov and 5.87 percent voted
against both of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
