<HEADLINE> Africa Backs Boutros-Ghali for Second-term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) has officially endorsed U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali for a second term.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced through a declaration of the
53-nation body in its three-day annual summit meeting in Yaounda
Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
The declaration, which was obtained by Xinhua in the U.N.
headquarters this morning, recalled in the first place that in the
Assembly of Heads of State and Government of late 1995 expressed
"appreciation to Boutros-Ghali for his initiative at the helm of
the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
It then reaffirmed the historic importance of the election of
an African as Secretary-General of the United Nations, "thus
enabling Africa to significantly contribute to the attainment of
the principles enshrined in the U.N. Charter and promote
multilateralism."
</P>
<P>
The African countries therefore "recommends that the necessary
steps be taken with all the partners, members of the U.N., to give
Africa a second mandate, for the next five years, and recommends
the candidature of Dr. Boutros Boutros-Ghali for a second term as
Secretary-General of the U.N."
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to veto the reappointment of
the 73-year-old Egyptian for a second five-year term, saying that
Boutros-Ghali has become an obstacle towards U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton Administration was not happy with his hesitation to
approve the nomination of Joseph Cornnor, an American professor,
to head the U.N. management department, to establish an internal
oversight office on waste and abuse of power and to approve the
1996-1997 zero growth budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
