<HEADLINE> UK Tube Strike Sets to Escalate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhu) -- Drivers of the London Underground
(LU) are to stage a further nine 24-hour strikes over the next two
months in their dispute over a shorter working week, their union,
Aslef, announced Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The union's executive agreed to cancel a strike called for next
Tuesday and to enter talks with London Transport at the Advisory
Conciliation and Arbitration Service (Acas), but set nine more
dates for 24-hour walkouts: July 18, 25 and 29; August 7, 13, 23
and 27; and September 5 and 9.
</P>
<P>
Tony West, assistant general secretary of the union said he
hoped the "serious escalation" of the industrial action would not
take place and the union regretted disruption caused by its three
one-day strikes so far over the last fortnight, but blamed LU for
reneging on a deal to cut the working week by one hour.
</P>
<P>
Ann Burfutt, London Transport's director of human resources,
said: "We are saddened that Aslef have notified us of further
dates for industrial action which could be linked to potential
action by the RMT (Rail, Maritime and Transport union). We do,
however, welcome the opportunity to get round the table at Acas."
</P>
</TEXT>
