<HEADLINE> UK Deserves to Be Semiconductor Capital of Europe, Lang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The UK electronics sector has earned
a world-wide reputation as a centre for excellence based on
innovation and quality.
</P>
<P>
Britain is now widely as the semiconductor capital of Europe
with more fabrication plants than any other country.
</P>
<P>
The success of the industry was highlighted today by the
publication of the Invest in Britain Bureau (IBB) Annual Review of
Operations 1996. The review shows that the UK is now home to
manufacturing plants for 11 of the world's 20 leading electronics
companies.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the electronics section of the review, President
of the Board of Trade, Ian Lang said: "The semiconductor capital
of Europe is an impressive title and, with over half of the
world's leading electronics companies based here and an
electronics industry worth an estimated 22 billion pounds (33
billion US dollars), it is one that the UK well deserves."
</P>
<P>
"In the past year we have seen electronics investment projects
coming to the UK from North America, Asia and continental Europe
bringing with them many thousands of skilled jobs," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
The electronics sector is vital to many other industries, such
as car manufacturing and telecommunications, where it has
benefited and contributed to their increased productivity.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Lang said, these supply chains would create real
opportunities for large numbers of British firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
