<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Ends With African Unity Strengthened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Guo Ming
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The 32nd summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), which closed here today amid
the solemn OAU anthem, adopted the Yaounde Declaration to prepare
the continent for entering the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony, attended by heads of state, government
chiefs and delegates from 53 OAU member countries as well as
hundreds of international observers, was presided over by hosting
Cameroonian President Paul Biya.
</P>
<P>
"Political stability and economic development are closely
knitted together. The continent could not enjoy peace and
development until war and conflict are resolved in every African
country," said President Biya who is also the current OAU
chairman.
</P>
<P>
After hours of hot debate, the three-day summit
meeting did not adopt any specific resolution on the continent's
"hot spots" including Rwanda, Burundi, Liberia, Somalia and
Sierra Leone, merely calling for all conflicting parties to
resort to peaceful means in acquiring national reconciliation and
regional stability.
</P>
<P>
In an upbeat touch, however, eight out of 11 countries in the
conflict-strife sub-region of central Africa signed a
non-aggression pact, strengthening the conflict prevention
mechanism in the area.
</P>
<P>
Economic issues were highlighted by the summit meeting during
which a total of 11 resolutions were adopted.
</P>
<P>
A decision was made by the summit to convene the Economic and
Social Committee (ECOSOC) by the end of October this year in a
bid to step up the process of economic integration and prepare
for the final establishment of the African Economic Community
(AEC).
</P>
<P>
Two economic resolutions were also adopted for the
African countries to take a common stance on relieving Africa's
unbearable external debt and ensuring food security in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Checking the spreading of HIV/AIDS, protecting the
environment, and enhancing education, medical care and women's
rights, etc., are among the social issues on which the OAU summit
has adopted resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to show the African unity, the OAU summit also passed
a collected decision on supporting Boutros Boutros-Ghali's
African candidature for a second term of office as the Secretary
General of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit also declared its "unwaiving support" to the
Palestinian struggle for peace and development, stressing the
importance of Afro-Arab friendship and cooperation, and urging
the continuation of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe was announced the next OAU
chairman, and the 33nd OAU summit will be held in the Zimbabwean
capital of Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
