<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in US Reaches 54.4 Bln Dlrs in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investments in
the United States totaled 54.4 billion dollars last year, marking
the continuous growth for the third straight year in this country.
</P>
<P>
In its recently released annual report on foreign investment,
the U.S. Commerce Department said direct spending by foreigners to
acquire or establish U.S. businesses shot up 19.2 percent from a
revised 1994 level of 45.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, in spite of the fact that the overall investment
marked the third straight annual increase, in percentage terms it
was far below the great jumps of 74 percent in 1994 and 71 percent
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Still, the advance pushed total investment for the year to the
highest level since 1990, when foreigners spent 65.9 billion
dollars acquiring U.S. business operations. The all-time high for
foreign investment in the U.S. was 72.7 billion dollars, set in
1988.
</P>
<P>
German companies recorded more than a fourfold increase last
year, pushing that country's total to 14.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For 1995, Japanese investment totaled 3.8 billion dollars, only
one-fifth of the country's 1990 peak of 19.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Britain was in second place last year with direct investment in
the United States totaling 9.7 billion dollars, a drop of 44
percent from its 1994 total.
</P>
<P>
Canada was ranked the third with new direct investment of 6.5
billion dollars, a 57 percent jump from 1994.
</P>
<P>
The government report attributed last year's overall increase
in part to a falling dollar. The dollar dropped to record lows
against both the Japanese yen and German mark in the early part of
the year. It also attributed part of the jump in foreign spending
last year to record-high levels for corporate profits, which
attracted overseas investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
