<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal's Population Aging Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lisbon, July 9 (xinhua) -- Portugal's population is aging
rapidly due to a falling birth rate and longer life expectancy,
said a report issued today by the National Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The result of the 1995 population census by the statistics
bureau showed that the total population of Portugal in 1995 was
9.92 million, of which, 14.7 percent were over 65, 17.6 percent
were under 14, and 67.7 percent were between 15 to 49.
</P>
<P>
The birth rate has fallen 36 percent since 1981, from an
average of 2.2 children per woman of child bearing age to 1.41
last year. And Portuguese women are waiting until they are older
before having children, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The average life expectancy of Portuguese men and women has
risen slightly since 1993. In 1994-95 men's life expectancy was
71.5 years, against 71.2 in 1993-94, while women's life expectancy
is 78.6 years against 78.2 in 1993-94, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has the lowest birth rate among European countries.
The birth rate needs to rise to 2.1 children before population
growth returns to normal, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
