<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Backs Neutrality of Sweden, Austria, Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) supported the neutrality maintained by Sweden,
Austria and Finland and their refusal to join the NATO, the
official newspaper Rodong Simon said today.
</P>
<P>
Without mentioning their names, the paper said some countries
alleged Austria, Sweden and Finland would join the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) after their entry into the European
Union (EU) in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the three countries had made clear their refusal
to participate in both the NATO and the Western European Union,
the EU's military arm and a link between the NATO and the EU.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang favors the three countries' neutrality which it
believes is helpful to their self-determination and European
security and peace, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the DPRK and the three European countries,
which were established "on the basis of self-determination and
inter-dependence", are developing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Like Sweden, Austria and Finland, the paper said, the DPRK also
highly values its right to self-determination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
