<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Step up Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Guo Ming
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- African leaders today moved to
step up economic integration in the continent by agreeing to
inaugurate an Economic and Social Committee (ECOSOC), the engine
to implement the African Economic Community (AEC) treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We have no more time to lose. The ECOSOC ministerial meeting
should be convened by October, 1996," said a resolution adopted
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU) 32nd heads of state
and government summit meeting which closed here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Abuja Treaty which came into effect on May
12, 1994, the community would be finally established by 2025,
five years after the creation of the African Common Market.
</P>
<P>
The ECOSOC meeting at expert level was convened on June 6-7 as
scheduled. But the ministerial meeting, being the inaugural
session of the ECOSOC, was postponed indefinitely, largely owing
to the lack of financial resources for the budget year in many
African countries ended in June.
</P>
<P>
As a result, important decisions and recommendations could not
be adopted as had been expected.
</P>
<P>
"But now, this unfavorable situation has changed," said Vijay
Makhan, OAU Deputy Secretary General in charge of economic affairs
and a devoted advocator of the economic integration in Africa, in
an interview with Xinhua today during the break of the OAU
summit.
</P>
<P>
"The decision is very important to step up the implementation
of the Abuja Treaty which decided to establish the AEC," said
Makhan, a 48-year-old Mauritius who is often soluted as "Mr. AEC"
(African Economic Community) for his long, devoted effort on
promoting Africans' AEC ideal.
</P>
<P>
"The political will is already there because the resolution
was adopted unanimously. Now, the question is, how to mobilize
all the necessary resources to support the integration process,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked what is the biggest challenge faced by Africa's AEC
endeavor, he said: "The unbearable burden of foreign debt."
</P>
<P>
Africa's foreign debt rose to a historical record of 320
billion US Dollars at the end of 1995, an increase of 18 billion
US Dollars compared to that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This debt constitutes 80 percent of the total gross domestic
product (GDP) in the continent, which has to pay up their annual
debt servicing duty with nearly 30 percent of their hard-to-earn
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign debt burden has greatly limited our ability to
mobilize the resources, and as a result, has prevented us from
carrying out many necessary tasks," he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
The OAU deputy secretary general criticized the western donors
as "doing too little" in solving Africa's foreign debt problem
and "trying to impose too many conditionalities" on African
countries in rescheduling their foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations on the debt issue at the just-concluded summit
meeting of the group of seven industrialized countries, "did not
make any substantial progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the OAU resolution adopted today by the summit
meeting, African leaders have also agreed to take a common stance
in solving the foreign debt problem facing the continent.
</P>
<P>
"That is the reality we have to face," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the present circumstances, the top priority is to
strengthen the sub-regional economic blocs which, according to
Makhan, is "the pillars of the AEC under construction."
</P>
<P>
The Mr. AEC also highlighted the urgent need to create a
regional information network to help promote the intra-Africa
trade which, during 1995, accounted for only 6 percent of the
total foreign trade volume of the African countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is something that I want to do most, at present time,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Makhan emphasized on the importance of attracting
foreign investment to Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said Africa, with its investment return rate of 30 percent
which is the highest in the world, should improve its environment
of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
And the OAU is now lobbying all over the world for foreign
investment, especially from the small-and-medium-sized foreign
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a need to publicize a good deal more about the
AEC so as to let more people understand, and lobby for more
support, for our cause," said Makhan.
</P>
<P>
"Year 2025. The blueprint of the AEC is there. Now comes the
hard part: to implement it, under all circumstances," said the
Mr. AEC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
