<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Gold Output Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Gold output in Zimbabwe rose four
percent to reach 12.17 tonnes worth 150 million US Dollars during
the first six months of this year, the Chamber of Mines of
Zimbabwe said today.
</P>
<P>
This compares with production during the first six months of
1995 which totalled 11.66 tonnes, then worth 120 million US
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The chamber, which has already projected annual gold output
might, for the first time, surpass 25 tonnes this year, was
disappointed that June's production of 1,862.53 kg had fallen
eight percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
"We don't really know what caused production to fall, but if
the trend continues, we might reach 25 tonnes," an official of
the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean gold mines were expected to sustain production on
the back of rising world demand.
</P>
<P>
Gold is currently the most lucrative investment sector of the
mining industry, which is the world's fifth largest industry
(including oil, gas and coal) in terms of capital deployed,
according to the World Gold Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
