<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Says It Holds Remains of Two Missing Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior officer of the Lebanese
pro-Iranian Hezbbllah, or Party of God, announced here today that
his party was holding the remains of two missing Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
But he denied that he knew the fate of Ron Arad, the Israeli
air force navigator who missed in southern Lebanon after his
plane was shot down in the area on October 16, 1986.
</P>
<P>
In a report on missing Israeli servicemen in southern Lebanon,
Israel said that it had convincing informations that two soldiers,
Yossi Fink and Rahamin Alsheikh, died after their capture by
Hezbollah guerrillas in an ambush in southern Lebanon on February
17, 1986.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in a Beirut office of the Shiite
 fundamentalist party this afternoon, Sheikh Naim Kassem, deputy
secretary general of Hezbollah, said that there were bodies of
two Israeli soldiers in his party's hand.
</P>
<P>
But he did not specify whether the two Israeli soldiers were
Yossi Fink and Rahamin Alsheikh.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed that the pilot might be alive and held by a
contingent of the Iranian revolutionary guards based in Beqaa
Valley in eastern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The three Israeli soldiers are among six missing in southern
Lebanon. The three others are Zachary Baumel, Zvi Feldman and
Yehuda Katz who disappeared on June 11, 1982 during a tank battle
with Syrian troops in the area and they reportedly were paraded
later in Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Israel has lost over 1,000 soldiers in southern Lebanon since
1982, including 19 died in the year.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference especially held to inaugurate
activities marking the Prisoners' Day, which falls on July 14,
the Hezbollah deputy secretary general repeated his party's
proposal of exchanging prisoners with Israel and the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture to underline its sincerity, Hezbollah released
today two SLA militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Kassem reiterated the proposal of exchanging the dozens of
militiamen captured by Hezbollah with those Lebanese detained in
a Israeli-controlled jail at Khiam in the Israeli occupied
"security zone" in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 prisoners are locked by Israel and its
client militia in the hilltop jail at Khiam under accusation
of collaborating with anti-Israeli guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
