<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Presents Preliminary Guidelines for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's next
multiannual "framework" research program should focus on six
priority areas and draw up simpler procedures for getting projects
off the ground, the European Commission(EC) said in a Communication
today.
</P>
<P>
The Communication which was adopted by the EC was intended to
open the debate on the fifth research and technological development
framework program which in 1999 will take over from the fourth
framework program now in progress.
</P>
<P>
EC's Research Commissioner Edith Cresson, who presented
preliminary guidelines for the Fifth Framework Program, told a
news conference that it was critical for the EU to narrow the
technological gap with the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is lagging behind and the gap is getting worse," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The EC's guideline propose that the Fifth Framework Program
concentrate on the following areas:
</P>
<P>
-- Unlocking the resources of living world and the ecosystem,
covering for example disease prevention and the use of technology to
protect the environment;
</P>
<P>
-- Creating a user-friendly information society;
</P>
<P>
-- Promoting competitive and sustainable growth, covering issues
such as product design, energy and transport efficiency and rural
development;
</P>
<P>
-- Improving human potential, or boosting the training and
mobility of scientists;
</P>
<P>
-- Innovation and participation of small and medium-sized
enterprises;
</P>
<P>
-- Confirming the international role of European research.
</P>
<P>
In implementing these priorities, substantial improvements need
to be made in the management of the research programs, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Mr Cresson also said that the EC first of all intended ensuring
greater flexibility in the work and the decision-making process,
entailing a streamlining of procedures.
</P>
<P>
For example, at the Intergovernmental Conference the EC will
advocate a simplified decision-making procedure with qualified
majority voting for the framework program and the specific
programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
