<HEADLINE> Contraceptive Users Increase in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The use of contraceptives,
which stood at 4 percent when the National Population Policy
(NPP) was launched three years ago, has now grown to 8 percent
through efforts made to implement the policy in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian National Population Office announced this in a
statement to mark the third anniversary celebration of the
launching of the NPP on July 12.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's population office head Negussie Tefera said population
offices opened in seven regional states are contributing much in
promoting family planning education among the people.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the population policy has faced no
resistance from mainstream religious, Negussie said, adding that
he had even witnessed the faithful receiving contraceptives while
returning from church attendance on Sabbath Day.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) has
increased its 19 million Dollars five-year assistance to
Ethiopia's population program to 29.3 million Dollars following a
review it has carried out on population policy implementation in
the regions.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has a population of 56 million. The national
population policy of the country was officially launched on July
12, 1993 to coincide with the World Population Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
