<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Inauguration to Take Place in Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A re-elected Boris Yeltsin will be
inaugurated on August 9 as the Russian president at the Kremlin's
Cathedral Square.
</P>
<P>
The swearing-in ceremony, presidential spokesman Sergei
Medvedev said today, will be participated by the leaders of the
other former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin became the first Russian president on July 10, 1991,
when he was sworn in before then Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
and the Supreme Soviet, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's second inauguration, Medvedev said, will be followed
by receptions in the ornate St. George's Hall and the 505-year-old
Hall of Facets.
</P>
<P>
Russia's recent presidential elections were carried out in two
rounds on June 16 and July 3.
</P>
<P>
During the first round, none of the 10 candidates got over 50
percent of votes, and the top two runners, Yeltsin and Zyuganov,
had to race in a run-off.
</P>
<P>
According to Russia's Central Electoral Commission on Tuesday,
a total of 74.81 million people, or 68.89 percent of registered
voters, took part in the second round of the voting.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 40.2 million, or 53.82 percent, cast their ballots for
Yeltsin, and 30.21 million, or 40.31 percent, voted for his
communist challenger Gennady Zyuganov. The remaining 5.87 percent
voted against both Yeltsin and Zyuganov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
