<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Fails to Adopt Resolution on Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The 32nd summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) today failed to adopt a
resolution on any of Africa's hot spots torn apart by years of
civil wars.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim told a press
conference following the conclusion of the summit that Burundi,
Rwanda, Liberia, Somalia and Sierra Leone, among other
conflict-ridden African countries remained the focal points under
discussion.
</P>
<P>
According the final communique made available to Xinhua after
the summit, a total of 11 resolutions had been adopted by the OAU
summit, but most of them were concerning the economic and social
issues.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Burundi, which occupied the largest share of
debate at closed-door talks, Salim said considerable progress has
been made in improving the situation there, adding the OAU summit
has voiced its continuous support to the mediation effort between
the Tutsi minority government and the majority Hutus by former
Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere and former United State
president Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
"We are still very concerned over the deterioting situation in
Burundi on which we will take necessary steps to ensure that
there is no repetition of the Rwandan tragedy," said Salim,
referring to the 1994 ethnic cleansing in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
The summit decided to continue the OAU observers mission in
Burundi, after ruling out military intervention into the central
African country which is on the verge of escalation of ethnic
conflict between the Tutsis and the Hutus, according to Salim.
</P>
<P>
He said there is nothing new about OAU's resolve over the
situation in Liberia where, despite the return to peace process
following the signing of the Abuja peace accord last August, a
new round of factional fighting occurred during April and May
this year.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit also stressed the need to strengthen west
Africa's peacekeeping force in Liberia, known as the ECOMOG, and
called for the mobilization of necessary resources to support the
ECOMOG mission.
</P>
<P>
The summit promised "not to abandon Somalia" and was
"encouraged to see that peace seems to be returning in the
grassroot of the war-torn country," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Somali delegation was, for the second time since
last year's OAU gathering, absent throughout the Council of
Ministers meeting and the summit, having been rejected by the
organisers beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Salim said the OAU summit was "kind of upbeat" about the
improved situation in Sierra Leone where two rounds of peaceful
general elections were held in February and March.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the newly elected civil government to narrow its
differences in disarmament and budget-sharing with the rebels,
the remaining two areas after agreement had been reached in
another 26 areas under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the press conference, Salim said although there
is not a single resolution on them, "there is still a need to
strengthen the OAU mechanism for conflict prevention, management
and resolution" which was established in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He urged for more contributions to the OAU peace fund by donors
in and outside Africa in a bid to enhance OAU's ability to resolve
conflicts in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
