<HEADLINE> UN Appoints New Head of its Mission to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali appointed Norbert Heinrich Holl (Germany) as
the new Head of the United Nations Special Mission to Afghanistan,
a U.N. spokeswoman announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman Sylvana Foa said that Holl succeeded Mahmoud
Mestiri, who resigned last May due to health reasons.
</P>
<P>
Until his new appointment, Holl, a German national, was the
Director for South Asia of the Federal Foreign Office in Bonn
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan, a landlocked country, was invaded by the former
Soviet Union in 1979 at the invitation of the government to put
down the widespread popular revolts. The Soviet troops were
withdrawn in early 1989. But, the fighting has continued since. In
the lasting civil war, 1.7 million people or 10 percent of the
population lost their lives and more were displaced.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations General Assembly adopted a resolution on
December 21, 1993, which requested the Secretary-General to
dispatch to Afghanistan a U.N. special mission to canvass a broad
spectrum of the leaders of Afghanistan, soliciting their views on
how the U.N. can best assist Afghanistan in facilitating the
national rapprochement and reconstruction. The U.N. special mission
headed by Mestiri began its work in Afghanistan in March 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
