<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Silent on Inter-state Conflicts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The closed-door summit meeting of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) kept silence on the
inter-state conflicts in Africa, OAU Secretary General Salim
Ahmed Salim said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference following the closing of the three-day
summit, Salim said the land dispute of the Bakassi peninsula
between Cameroon and Nigeria, and the refugee dispute between
Rwanda and Zaire, "were neither on the OAU summit agenda nor
being neglected."
</P>
<P>
"On the question of inter-state conflict, the less noise made,
the more helpful," said Salim.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief criticized some media for exaggerating the
conflicts, leading to the worsening of the situation.
</P>
<P>
The OAU hoped that the related countries could solve their own
problems without "interference or intervention" by the regional
body, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Bakassi issue, Salim said the dispute had already been
submitted to the United Nations international court of justice in
the Hague, "so there is no sense in fussing about it any more" at
the OAU forum.
</P>
<P>
Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema, entrusted by the OAU,
is continuing to play his mediation role between Nigeria and
Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha, who did not attend
the OAU summit meeting held in the Cameroonian capital of
Yaounde, said earlier that he was not willing to discuss the
Bakassi issue at the OAU forum, as insisted by the Cameroonian
government.
</P>
<P>
On the Rwanda-Zaire dispute on refugees, Salim said at the
present stage, it would be better that the issue be resolved by
the relative parties themselves.
</P>
<P>
There was quite a bit of fingerpointing at each other between
the two delegations to the OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
The Zairese delegates threathened the use of force against the
Rwandan refugees in its territory while the Rwandan delegates
retorted "nonsense", saying the Tutsi-dominated Kigali government
is ready to receive the Hutu refugees without any problem.
</P>
<P>
After much hot debate during the closed-door session, the OAU
summit chose to keep silence on the issue without adopting any
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to watch closely over the situations there,"
said Salim, the OAU chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
