<HEADLINE> Roundup: Netanyahu's Hardline Statements in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Party, Israel's
opposition party, today charged Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
had in fact closed peace options in the Middle East during his
current visit to the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Moshe Shahal, a Labor Party's member of the Knesset (Israel's
parliament), said that Netanyahu has approved that he is more
connected with his slogans during the elections than to be a
premier trying to solve problems.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who held talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton in
Washington Tuesday, reportedly made no concessions neither on
the Palestinian-related issues, nor on the negotiations with the
Syrians.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the U.S. congress today, the Israeli prime minister
repeated his hardline positions toward the peace process, and
made no mention of any compromises in the peace talks with
Israel's Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Shahal, internal minister in the previous Labor government,
said relations between Israel and its Arab neighbors are in
danger, adding that new terrorist activities may go to take place
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his concerns about "what is going to happen
between Israel and Syria, specially if there will be a disharmony
between Israel and the U.S. administration."
</P>
<P>
Hagai Meirom, another Labor Knesset member, indicated that the
Israeli-U.S. relations would also meet obstacles as the
U.S. would pressure Israel if there is no progress in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Syrian and Egyptian newspapers today have blasted
Netanyahu for what they termed as his uncompromising positions in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian official newspaper Tishreen said that Netanyahu
presented nothing new in his discussions with Clinton, and even
did not demonstrate intention regarding of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The paper accused the Israeli prime minister of addressing
Arab with arrogance, and with some languages used by Adolf Hitler
during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian newspaper Al-Akhbar warned of the limits of Arab
patience, saying that Netanyahu's recent remarks are provocative,
and that "he is wrong if he thinks he can scare Arabs to
capitulate to Israel's control."
</P>
