<HEADLINE> Formation of Unified Army in Angola Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The work to integrate Angola's
former UNITA rebels into a unified army was suspended today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by General Joao De Matos, the Chief
of General Staff of the Angolan armed forces here today.
</P>
<P>
Joao De Matos said the Angolan government has also decided to
withdraw its technical personnel who are working in the assembly
points of the UNITA troops.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made because the UNITA "is not earnest in
solving a problem of vital importance to the state," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, the peace process in Angola is irreversible and
the suspension of the formation of the unified army is a
setback only, not a breakdown.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the unified army started on July 1.
Under an initial plan, 26,000 of the 52,000 UNITA soldiers in
the assembly points should be integrated in the unified army.
