<HEADLINE> Russian Troops Bombed Chechen Rebel Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian troops were shelling and
bombing two villages in Chechnya today, including the one
presumably sheltering the rebel headquarters.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass news agency and Interfax news agency
reports, air and artillery forces were used in the escalated
fighting to deliver strikes to the villages of Makhety and Gekhi.
</P>
<P>
Makhety, 35 kilometers south of the Chechen regional capital of
Grozny, is believed to be the site of the headquarters of
separatist leader Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev.
</P>
<P>
And Gekhi, in southwestern Chechnya, is a strongly
pro-separatist village.
</P>
<P>
The renewed fighting, beginning Tuesday, took place six weeks
after the warring parties signed a peace pact in the Kremlin and a
week after President Boris Yeltsin's re-election.
</P>
<P>
Major Igor Melnikov, a Russian military spokesman in Chechnya,
was quoted as denying that civilians were being targeted in the
offensives by federal troops.
</P>
<P>
However, local officials said that at least 20 civilians were
killed and many others wounded in Mahkety today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier government reports said that eight Russian soldiers
were killed and about 20 more injuried in Gekhi on Tuesday, in
addition to more than 10 deaths on the rebel side.
</P>
<P>
None of the casualties could be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 people had been killed in the 19-month-old
conflict in the breakaway republic before Yeltsin and Yandarbiyev
arranged a truce and agreed to exchange prisoners.
</P>
<P>
In his explanation today, Melnikov said the attack on Makhety
was not a violation of the May 27 agreement but merely a response
to violations from the rebel side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
