<DOCNO> XIE19960711.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-10 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Netanyahu's Hardline Statements in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the Gaza strip, Palestinian National Authority (PNA)'s
Local Government Minister Saeb Erekat said today that the peace
process is beginning "to slip through our fingers."
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that while Netanyahu was speaking peace in
English, but when it comes to implementing the agreement, he
gives entirely different instructions in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Zaki, a member of the Palestinian Council, said that
Netanyahu was ignoring Palestinian concerns, and that the PNA
will not be able to control the anger of the people.
</P>
<P>
He also warned of a possible upgrade of renewal of the
Intifada (Palestinian uprising in the late 1980s).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, dozens of Palestinian residents of Hebron clashed
with Israeli troops this morning to protest the delay of Israel's
redeployment in the disputed West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
A pipebomb was thrown at an Israeli roadblock in the police
square in the center of Hebron, Israeli bomb explosive experts
rushed to the scene and detonated the device in a controlled
explosion.
</P>
<P>
The clash reportedly lasted for an hour, as Palestinian youths
threw stones and bottles at the Israeli soldiers before they were
finally dispersed by the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The army then sealed off the area, shutting down shops in the
market areas, and imposing a curfew.
</P>
<P>
No injury or damage was reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oslo 2 accord signed between Israel and the
Palestinians, the Israeli army was supposed to pullback from about
85 percent of Hebron by March 28. However, the redeployment was
delayed following a series of suicide bombing attacks against
Israelis in late February and early March, which killed 62 people.
</P>
<P>
In May, the former Israeli government led by Shimon Peres
announced that the army's withdrawal from Hebron would be carried
out after the May 29 general elections, due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, Peres, defeated by Netanyahu, said after the
elections that he would leave the decision of the redeployment to
the new prime minister and his government.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, some 30 kilometers southwest of Jerusalem, is a place
of pilgrimage for Christians, Jews and Moslems alike, and
tradition has it that patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob and their
wives are all buried in the Machpelah Cave (Haram al-Khalil).
</P>
<P>
There are some 400 Jewish settlers now living in the center of
Hebron, who moved back to the city's old Jewish neighborhood after
the 1967 Middle East War, during which Israel took over the town
from the Jordanian authority.
</P>
<P>
Surrounding the Jewish community, there are more than 200,000
Palestinian residents living in most other parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
During his election campaign, Netanyahu had said that he would
like Hebron to be part of the final status arrangements with the
Palestinians, but, at the same time, he also said he would stand
by the international agreements.
</P>
<P>
So far, Netanyahu repeatedly said he has been studying the
issue of the redeployment in Hebron, but giving no date when he
would make the final decision.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio today quoted American sources as saying that the
Israeli premier Tuesday told Clinton at their private meeting
that he would seek a way to implement the redeployment in
Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
