<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Criticizes Netanyahu's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid today criticized Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu for his remarks at a joint press conference with
U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference here with Henry Siegman,
Director of the U.S./Middle East Project at the New York-based
Council on Foreign Relations, Abdul-Meguid said that the press
conference at the White House was "not encouraging."
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel must withdraw from all occupied Arab land
before a just and comprehensive peace can be reached. This would
include Syria's Golan Heights, the West Bank and Gaza Strip, south
Lebanon and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu is playing with fire and he will burn himself first
before anyone else," the Arab League chief said.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs are committed to U.N. Security Council resolutions as
well as the land-for-peace principle, he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, at the White House news conference, challenged the
land-for-peace formula as the only basis for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel has a different view of U.N. Security
Council resolution 242, which urged Israel to return land seized
in the 1967 Mideast war in exchange for peace. He maintained
Israel has made "substantial concessions on all fronts."
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid co-chaired with Siegman, a Middle East specialist,
a two-day seminar on Arab-U.S. relations which ended here Tuesday.
</P>
