<HEADLINE> Turkey's First Kurdish TV Starts Broadcasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A privately-owned television
channel, CAN TV, started today regular broadcasting in Kurdish,
becoming the first of its kind in the history of the highly
Kurdish populated southeast of Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Nevzat Bingol, owner of the CAN TV based in
southeastern Diyarbakir, as saying that their broadcasting was
limited to only several hours a day. But he added that they wanted
to expand the broadcasting to 24 hours a day in the future.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being we only have music programs in
Kurdish. Music is universal. And, I don't suppose that anyone can
claim that we are propagating separatism because we let people
listen to music in Kurdish. Music has no language," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the current Turkish legislation regarding the use
of Kurdish, Bingol said that Kurdish was not actually illegal.
</P>
<P>
"We want to have a law which will make it clear what
is illegal and what is legal. We are definitely ready to act in
line with it later on," he noted. 
</P>
