<HEADLINE> Namibian Agriculture Faces Serious Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's agriculture
industry is facing serious financial problems and needs
international assistance, the South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said Namibian Finance Minister Helmut Angula has
invited the Namibian Agruculture Union (NAU) to an urgent meeting
to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
NAU Executive Chairman Jan De Wet was quoted as saying few
commercial farmers would be able to survive without international
aid to, at least, subsidiZe interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the number of the beef cattle in
Namibia has declined by 56 percent from the previous 2 million
head to the present 870,000. Small stock has seen a decrease from
4 million head to 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Commercial farmers, however, have seen their debt increased
by nearly 50 percent in the past five years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the past 50 years, the land's carrying capacity has been weakened by
between 40 and 50 percent and there has been an alarming drop in the water
table. Labour and production costs have soared by between 100 and 500
percent, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
