<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Legislation Against Church Arson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today praised a new law to prevent church arson, saying a
significant number of recent fires at places of worship were
racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
At a Rose Garden ceremony heralding the Church Arson Prevention
Act he signed last week, Clinton said, "We have to continue our
struggle against racism and religious bigotry."
</P>
<P>
The new law makes the destruction of places of worship a
federal crime.
</P>
<P>
Calling the burning of churches an "outrage," Clinton said that
since January of 1995, more than 190 incidents of fire or
desecration of houses of places of worship have been reported in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said while many have been targeted at black churches in the
South, there have also been attacks on synagogues, mosques, and
white churches in all parts of this country.
</P>
<P>
More arrests are being made and in the last three weeks, there
have been arrests in connection with fires in North Carolina,
South Carolina, Texas, Virginia, Washington and Missouri, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new law doubles the maximum penalty for the crimes that
cause injury to people and increases the statute of limitations
from five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said several government agencies have been mobilized to
prosecute arsonists, prevent burnings, and help communities
rebuild. 
</P>
</TEXT>
