<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two   Million Children Suffer From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- An estimated two million children
in Nigeria, aged between five and 14, are infected with
schistosomiasis, Minister of Health Ihechukwu Madubuike said here
today.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on ''schistosomiasis control'', the minister said
the disease is prevalent in the northernmost part of the country
and affecting the rural and urban communities with poor sanitary
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The use of earth dams for irrigation and domestic purposes
predisposes the people to the disease usually carried by snails
which are everywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the disease on children, according to the
minister, is felt on reduced growth and development as well as
malnutrition. It could result in hypertension, infertility and
cancer of the bladder.
</P>
<P>
The government started a national schistosomiasis control
program as early as in 1988 to bring the disease under control,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Children's Fund and Global 2000 are
initiating efforts to support the program, he said, adding that
the World Health Organisation is providing technical support.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, there is a bright future for the coordinated
efforts to control the disease, he said.  enditem

