<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Says Jerusalem Not to Be Redivided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu declared today that Israel will not allow Jerusalem to
be redivided between Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the U.S. Congress, Netanyahu said, "There have
been efforts to redivide this city by those who claim that peace
can come through division, that it can be secured through multiple
sovereignties, multiple laws and multiple police forces."
</P>
<P>
"This is a groundless and dangerous assumption, and it impels
me to declare today there will never be such a redivision of
Jerusalem," he pounded the lectern in the House of Representatives
for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem has been a holy city to Arabs, Jews and Christians
alike and its eastern part, the Arabs' residential quarter, was
occupies by Israeli forces in the 1967 war with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Israeli authorities have ever since declared Jerusalem as
Israel's capital, but the United States and most other nations do
not recognize it as such.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat quickly
reacted in Gaza to Netanyahy's statement by accusing him of
"lying" about the Palestinian position on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"It's a pity that Mr Netanyahu begs the sympathy of the
Congress by lying on the Palestinian position on Jerusalem," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the allegation Netanyahu made in the Congress that
the Palestinians intend to erect within Jerusalem "a Berlin
Wall," the spokesman said, "President Arafat and the Palestinian
Authority do not want to divide the city, do not want to build a
wall, do not want to put up barbed wires."
</P>
<P>
"They want a unified city, the capital for two peoples and
this is the time that the president (Arafat) feels that he would
stress the right of the Palestinians in Jerusalem, the city and
the capital of the coming Palestinian State," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
