<HEADLINE> Citroen to Transfer Know-How Program to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Automobile Citroen, one of France's
two leading auto producers, today announced a plan to transfer its
technological know-how training programs for China from the home
base to that country.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Billon, head of the Quality and Management Department at
the Training Center of Institute Citroen in Saint-Ouen, northwest
Paris, said that Citroen will build in September a training center
in Wuhan by copying the one here in Paris, for the joint venture
Dong Feng Citroen Automobile Company (DCAC) in Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of DCAC in 1992, which produces
Citroen's ZX cars that are named "Fu Kang" in China, all training
programs have been made in Paris.
</P>
<P>
About 500 Chinese trainees have since 1993 joined the programs
on integrating the terminal factory in Wuhan with the mechanical
factory in Xiangfan, which are 1,000 kilometers away from each
other in Hubei, said Citroen officials.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is that the two factories will be completely
automonous from 1997," said Billon, adding that "from production
to sale, all aspects of training will be put under one roof" in
the planned training center in Wuhan with 500,000 training hours
expected for the first two years.
</P>
<P>
He also said Citroen will send 50 cadres to China to make sure
of the success of the Wuhan center and Citroen plans to expand its
factory in Wuhan to the size of that in Aulnay-sous-Bois in
Seine-Saint-Denis in Paris with about 8,000 personnel.
</P>
<P>
Citroen will invest 7.5 billion francs (1.5 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first phase of the construction of DCAC, said
Billion, adding that the factory should produce 150,000 vehicles
in 1997 and 300,000 in the following year.
</P>
<P>
Calling the previous plan "an action of foundation," Philippe
Roch, head of Human Resources of China Program of Citroen, said
that the corporation does not expect much profit in the first 10
years from DCAC.
</P>
<P>
"The two keys to success are a transfer of tested technology
and a good integration of the two local factories," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
