<HEADLINE> Ghali Assured Africa of "UN Special Initiative" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali today assured Africa of the UN special
initiative which he said they can depend on.
</P>
<P>
Ghali was nominated as the African candidate for the second
term of his office at the just-concluded 32nd summit meeting of
the organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"You can depend on the whole system of the United Nations. And
you can depend on me," Ghali, who gave full attendance to the
three-day OAU summit meeting which closed here today, told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief arrived in Yaounde last Saturday to attend the
OAU summit meeting as a special guest. He is also here seeking
support for his second term as UN Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
On March 15, Ghali and World Bank President James Wolfensohn
co-unveiled the UN "special initiative on Africa", a 10-year
investment plan for the continent worth 25 billion US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the wide-ranged plan includes strengthening OAU's
capacity in the mechanism for conflict prevention, management and
resolution, reducing Africa's external debt, boosting foreign
investment in Africa and enhancing Africa's export capabilities.
</P>
<P>
It also deals with food security and drought management by
improving soil quality, and promoting control of land degradation
and desertification.
</P>
<P>
"The program involves all the u.n. agencies, together with the
World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, the International
Agricultural Development fund, etc.," said Ghali.
</P>
<P>
"And we are expecting full participation of all the OAU member
countries to ensure success of the program," said the UN chief.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat said, "Ghali promised his full consideration of and
support for the interest of the African continent, and the OAU
members owe their trust in him."
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, United States Assistant Secretary of State
George Moose arrived in Yaounde in a bid to persuade some of the
African leaders into voting against Ghali's candidature.
</P>
<P>
"Moose's lobby mission totally failed," said another diplomat.
</P>
</TEXT>
