<HEADLINE> Social Issues Addressed in OAU Summit Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- African social issues, such as
HIV/AIDS, environment and education, have been addressed by the
32nd summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, which ended here today, adopted four
resolutions on those issues.
</P>
<P>
-- The resolution on hiv/aids in Africa requests the OAU
member countries to take urgent measures to check the further
worsening situation of the HIV/AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
It annouced that the first African Youth Conference on Sexual
Health under the theme of "the youth and AIDS: challenge for the
21st century" would be open in Accra, Ghana, from September 30 to
October 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
There are 12 million people infected with AIDS in the
sub-Sarahan Africa today.
</P>
<P>
-- The resolution on environment urges OAU member countries to
send representative missions to the United Nations Environment
Program (unep) and the United Nations Center for Human
Settlements (HABITAT) where such missions are not yet existent.
</P>
<P>
It calls upon sub-regional bodies in Africa such as ECOWAS,
COMESA, SADC and EAC to work closely with OAU member states to
ensure sustained efforts at strengthening the UNEP and the
HABITAT.
</P>
<P>
-- The resolution on education launches the Decade of
Education in Africa which covers the period from 1997 to 2006.
Eradication of illitracy is the major cause of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
-- The resolution on the African commission on human and
people's rights makes an appeal member states to ratify the
African charter on human and people's rights which came into
force on October 21, 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
