<HEADLINE> Refugees in Yugoslavia Face Serious Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The humanitarian situation of
refugees and their host families in Yugoslavia is very serious due
to lack of international aid, Yugoslav refugee officials said
today.
</P>
<P>
The 700,000 refugees living in this country is now having the
toughest situation over all the past five years, Serbian
Commissioner for Refugees Bratislava Morina said.
</P>
<P>
Morina made the remarks at a joint meeting in Belgrade with
Serbian Red Cross President Slobodanka Gruden and Yugoslav Red
Cross General Secretary Rade Dubajic to discuss the serious
situation of the refugees, according to the Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, they all agreed that it was necessary to warn
both the domestic society and the international community about
the huge problems in providing aid to the 700,000 refugees, of
whom the majority have found shelter with relatives and friends in
Yugoslavia, which consists of Serbia and Montenegro, Tanjug
reported.
</P>
<P>
Gruden and Dubajic said their primary task was to find a way to
secure food and personal hygiene packages, because the European
Union's Humanitarian Office has this month stopped sending aid for
refugees in private accommodations.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the situation in collective accommodation
centers was also alarming since there were no means for maintaining
these facilities.
</P>
<P>
A recent census held in Yugoslavia showed that there are
700,000 refugees from former Yugoslav republics now living in
Serbia, which has imposed a heavy economic and social burden on
the country which has suffered greatly from three-and-half-year
international sanctions that were suspended in December last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
